1
00:00:06,214 --> 00:00:11,553
<i>- Just go!
- Come quickly!</i>

2
00:00:13,179 --> 00:00:14,723
Keep going!

3
00:00:17,767 --> 00:00:18,767
What was that?

4
00:00:18,768 --> 00:00:21,021
Lock it!

5
00:00:26,109 --> 00:00:27,568
<i>In this adventure reality show,</i>

6
00:00:27,569 --> 00:00:31,656
<i>six cast members will become field agents
for a mysterious organization,</i>

7
00:00:32,365 --> 00:00:39,247
<i>diving into bizarre and supernatural cases
to carry out their missions.</i>

8
00:00:40,123 --> 00:00:41,374
What is that?

9
00:00:41,875 --> 00:00:45,377
<i>The mysterious cases,
locations, and missions</i>

10
00:00:45,378 --> 00:00:48,006
<i>have all been meticulously planned
by the creators.</i>

11
00:00:49,382 --> 00:00:55,429
<i>But the six members
are not given any prior information.</i>

12
00:00:55,430 --> 00:00:57,265
- It's coming out.
- Someone's here!

13
00:01:02,520 --> 00:01:05,314
<i>These situations are a reality to them,</i>

14
00:01:05,315 --> 00:01:09,526
<i>and they must take on their cases as such.</i>

15
00:01:09,527 --> 00:01:10,653
A bit faster.

16
00:01:11,863 --> 00:01:14,823
<i>Stay tuned to see them in action.</i>

17
00:01:14,824 --> 00:01:16,658
- Come in!
- Slowly.

18
00:01:16,659 --> 00:01:17,576
I found it.

19
00:01:17,577 --> 00:01:18,494
It's opening.

20
00:01:18,495 --> 00:01:19,454
Figure it out fast.

21
00:01:30,590 --> 00:01:32,257
Here we are again.

22
00:01:32,258 --> 00:01:33,510
The smell of the place.

23
00:01:34,427 --> 00:01:35,719
It was this smell.

24
00:01:35,720 --> 00:01:37,430
- We're back.
- Yes, we are.

25
00:01:39,182 --> 00:01:40,432
Oh, gosh.

26
00:01:40,433 --> 00:01:42,059
We've got this.

27
00:01:42,060 --> 00:01:44,686
Let's not lose heart even if we mess up.

28
00:01:44,687 --> 00:01:45,604
Let's keep going.

29
00:01:45,605 --> 00:01:46,855
Let's go.

30
00:01:46,856 --> 00:01:48,857
A LEADER BY EXAMPLE

31
00:01:48,858 --> 00:01:50,859
I think we'll stick together.

32
00:01:50,860 --> 00:01:53,362
- Do you want to change?
- Shouldn't it be ladies first?

33
00:01:53,363 --> 00:01:55,072
Why did you lose focus, Do-hoon?

34
00:01:55,073 --> 00:01:57,075
I won't accept any more mistakes.

35
00:01:59,869 --> 00:02:01,079
JUST YOUR DOWN-TO-EARTH OLD BROTHER

36
00:02:01,663 --> 00:02:03,080
LEE YONG-JIN

37
00:02:03,081 --> 00:02:04,540
- Do you remember?
- Yes.

38
00:02:04,541 --> 00:02:07,584
- Remember the pagan worshippers?
- The pagans.

39
00:02:07,585 --> 00:02:09,670
FROM SEASON 1
WAGON BROTHERS AND THE PAGANS

40
00:02:09,671 --> 00:02:11,338
- The followers.
- Yes.

41
00:02:11,339 --> 00:02:12,923
- There was also--
- The submarine.

42
00:02:12,924 --> 00:02:13,841
Yes, the submarine.

43
00:02:13,842 --> 00:02:14,883
POURING WATER

44
00:02:14,884 --> 00:02:17,094
Behold, close the cockpit's
emergency partition!

45
00:02:17,095 --> 00:02:20,139
- It smells a bit different.
- It does.

46
00:02:20,140 --> 00:02:21,181
It was winter then.

47
00:02:21,182 --> 00:02:22,891
- Is your wrist okay?
- I'm fine.

48
00:02:22,892 --> 00:02:24,769
You're our ace player.

49
00:02:25,395 --> 00:02:26,854
ACE OF ACCIDENTS

50
00:02:26,855 --> 00:02:28,231
<i>Do-hoon broke something again.</i>

51
00:02:30,066 --> 00:02:31,150
<i>Hey, Little Scaredy-cats.</i>

52
00:02:31,151 --> 00:02:32,276
Little Scaredy-cats? Me?

53
00:02:32,277 --> 00:02:33,735
- Let's go together.
- You rascal.

54
00:02:33,736 --> 00:02:36,864
A SCAREDY-CAT

55
00:02:36,865 --> 00:02:37,824
Come over here.

56
00:02:39,284 --> 00:02:40,826
BUT STILL A GENTLEMAN

57
00:02:40,827 --> 00:02:42,035
Do-hoon, you're so cool.

58
00:02:42,036 --> 00:02:43,370
I'm scared too.

59
00:02:43,371 --> 00:02:44,872
KIM DO-HOON

60
00:02:44,873 --> 00:02:47,416
It's been too long. Two years, right?

61
00:02:47,417 --> 00:02:50,043
- Yes, two years.
- Right?

62
00:02:50,044 --> 00:02:52,963
- Unbelievable.
- It's like a different era.

63
00:02:52,964 --> 00:02:56,717
Last night in bed,
I pictured possible scenarios for today.

64
00:02:56,718 --> 00:02:59,970
- Hello.
- Oh, hey.

65
00:02:59,971 --> 00:03:01,680
Look who it is.

66
00:03:01,681 --> 00:03:03,056
- Hello.
- This is so weird.

67
00:03:03,057 --> 00:03:05,183
I can't believe it, can you?

68
00:03:05,184 --> 00:03:07,311
- It's been so long.
- But it feels like yesterday.

69
00:03:07,312 --> 00:03:08,562
<i>We have Hye-ri.</i>

70
00:03:08,563 --> 00:03:10,898
Great job, Hye-ri.

71
00:03:10,899 --> 00:03:14,776
LEAD PROBLEM-SOLVER

72
00:03:14,777 --> 00:03:16,194
This is suspicious.

73
00:03:16,195 --> 00:03:18,655
- It could be the traitor.
- Traitor.

74
00:03:18,656 --> 00:03:20,741
- It's you, isn't it?
- No!

75
00:03:20,742 --> 00:03:21,868
HYE-RI

76
00:03:23,369 --> 00:03:24,828
- It opened.
- It did?

77
00:03:24,829 --> 00:03:26,414
PUZZLE SKILLS AS SHARP AS EVER

78
00:03:30,084 --> 00:03:31,710
I couldn't hear it. I didn't get anything.

79
00:03:31,711 --> 00:03:33,629
Be honest.
Have you lost your English skills?

80
00:03:33,630 --> 00:03:35,297
REGRESSING LANGUAGE SKILLS

81
00:03:35,298 --> 00:03:37,633
BEAT-DRIVEN FOOTWORK

82
00:03:37,634 --> 00:03:39,843
- Call him "Dancing Park."
- John's amazing.

83
00:03:39,844 --> 00:03:41,179
JOHN PARK

84
00:03:42,555 --> 00:03:43,932
I'm scared.

85
00:03:45,058 --> 00:03:47,226
THE SCAREDY-CAT OF THE GROUP

86
00:03:47,227 --> 00:03:48,560
Would you like to go first?

87
00:03:48,561 --> 00:03:50,270
NOT AFRAID OF THE OTHER MEMBERS

88
00:03:50,271 --> 00:03:51,231
My disciple.

89
00:03:53,358 --> 00:03:55,526
THE YOUNGEST WON'T HOLD BACK

90
00:03:56,653 --> 00:03:58,028
Keep a sick bag handy.

91
00:03:58,029 --> 00:03:58,946
It's in my bag.

92
00:03:58,947 --> 00:04:01,199
MAINTAINING HER DUTY AS TEAM PORTER

93
00:04:02,075 --> 00:04:04,202
KARINA

94
00:04:04,827 --> 00:04:06,203
Karina's started working out.

95
00:04:06,204 --> 00:04:07,246
- I go to the gym.
- Why?

96
00:04:07,247 --> 00:04:08,538
- So I can carry the items.
- Really?

97
00:04:08,539 --> 00:04:09,915
Will you be the team porter again?

98
00:04:09,916 --> 00:04:10,958
I can lift weights now.

99
00:04:10,959 --> 00:04:12,418
- You're lifting weights?
- Yes.

100
00:04:13,544 --> 00:04:16,838
- Why is your name tag in Korean?
- Is that necessary?

101
00:04:16,839 --> 00:04:17,923
- He's right.
- What?

102
00:04:17,924 --> 00:04:18,966
- What?
- You're right.

103
00:04:18,967 --> 00:04:20,717
- You should have a J.
- Why is yours English?

104
00:04:20,718 --> 00:04:22,761
Why isn't yours the letter P?

105
00:04:22,762 --> 00:04:24,388
There must be a reason.

106
00:04:24,389 --> 00:04:26,640
Yes, this can't just be by chance.

107
00:04:26,641 --> 00:04:28,643
That takes more effort
to make than the letter P.

108
00:04:29,435 --> 00:04:31,645
- It takes more stitches.
- It's more effort.

109
00:04:31,646 --> 00:04:32,562
I'm a bit jealous.

110
00:04:32,563 --> 00:04:34,273
- There must be a reason.
- It seems special.

111
00:04:34,274 --> 00:04:35,358
Ours are all--

112
00:04:38,069 --> 00:04:40,195
A CONFIDENT NEW MEMBER ARRIVES

113
00:04:40,196 --> 00:04:43,407
LAUGHING

114
00:04:43,408 --> 00:04:47,035
LOOK AT HER PEARLY WHITES

115
00:04:47,036 --> 00:04:49,538
It's so dark in here,
but all I see is your teeth.

116
00:04:49,539 --> 00:04:51,958
SELF-RADIATING NEW MEMBER

117
00:04:54,210 --> 00:04:57,296
WITH A LOUD VOICE

118
00:04:57,297 --> 00:04:58,631
Something feels off.

119
00:04:59,340 --> 00:05:00,424
Something's strange.

120
00:05:00,425 --> 00:05:02,467
Wait, could this be a signal?

121
00:05:02,468 --> 00:05:03,760
You're like a sniffer dog.

122
00:05:03,761 --> 00:05:05,595
INSTINCTIVE SENSING ABILITIES

123
00:05:05,596 --> 00:05:06,513
Seven, eight.

124
00:05:06,514 --> 00:05:08,015
- You can do it!
- You can do it!

125
00:05:08,016 --> 00:05:09,475
QUEEN OF CONSTANT ENERGY

126
00:05:10,226 --> 00:05:11,644
GABEE

127
00:05:13,021 --> 00:05:16,898
- Gabee, stay there for a second.
- Here?

128
00:05:16,899 --> 00:05:18,442
Doesn't she look like a US prisoner?

129
00:05:18,443 --> 00:05:19,359
US PRISON VIBES

130
00:05:19,360 --> 00:05:20,777
Look at you.

131
00:05:20,778 --> 00:05:23,155
- She just appeared.
- Let me out!

132
00:05:23,156 --> 00:05:24,824
And she gave off US prison vibes.

133
00:05:25,533 --> 00:05:26,492
Hello.

134
00:05:28,286 --> 00:05:30,120
A NEW MEMBER TO ADD TO THE EXCITEMENT

135
00:05:30,121 --> 00:05:32,539
This is going to be so much fun.

136
00:05:32,540 --> 00:05:33,790
It's nice to meet you.

137
00:05:33,791 --> 00:05:36,084
Gabee, are you good at this stuff?

138
00:05:36,085 --> 00:05:37,878
When I've done escape rooms,

139
00:05:37,879 --> 00:05:39,796
I wasn't able to do much.

140
00:05:39,797 --> 00:05:42,257
But I get really immersed.

141
00:05:42,258 --> 00:05:44,176
- You get pretty into it?
- Yes.

142
00:05:44,177 --> 00:05:46,678
I might cry if it gets too scary.

143
00:05:46,679 --> 00:05:48,680
Don't leave me on my own.

144
00:05:48,681 --> 00:05:50,223
- You scare easily?
- I do.

145
00:05:50,224 --> 00:05:51,808
- I see.
- Really?

146
00:05:51,809 --> 00:05:54,853
- You can stick with Do-hoon.
- You can rely on me, Gabee.

147
00:05:54,854 --> 00:05:56,855
I'm a coward too.

148
00:05:56,856 --> 00:05:58,690
He's our biggest wimp.

149
00:05:58,691 --> 00:05:59,816
I'm so excited.

150
00:05:59,817 --> 00:06:02,194
It feels good to have a new member.

151
00:06:02,195 --> 00:06:04,905
I want to start finding clues
now that we're here.

152
00:06:04,906 --> 00:06:06,656
This is just the headquarters.

153
00:06:06,657 --> 00:06:08,158
This was always here, right?

154
00:06:08,159 --> 00:06:09,242
- It was.
- Wherever we--

155
00:06:09,243 --> 00:06:13,663
<i>- Hello, agents.</i>
- That scared me!

156
00:06:13,664 --> 00:06:16,458
<i>Welcome back to the XIN,</i>

157
00:06:16,459 --> 00:06:20,378
<i>a top-secret organization
that detects and solves</i>

158
00:06:20,379 --> 00:06:23,715
<i>all mysterious phenomena in this world.</i>

159
00:06:23,716 --> 00:06:25,343
Here we go.

160
00:06:27,053 --> 00:06:29,555
<i>I will now brief you on your mission.</i>

161
00:06:30,515 --> 00:06:31,890
<i>Six months ago,</i>

162
00:06:31,891 --> 00:06:36,686
<i>a 43-meter-wide object plummeted
onto the coastline of southern Florida.</i>

163
00:06:36,687 --> 00:06:40,857
<i>This triggered
a massive tsunami in the area</i>

164
00:06:40,858 --> 00:06:42,777
<i>that resulted in many casualties.</i>

165
00:06:44,403 --> 00:06:48,907
<i>The US government told the media
the object was asteroid debris</i>

166
00:06:48,908 --> 00:06:51,993
<i>that had collided
with the Earth's atmosphere.</i>

167
00:06:51,994 --> 00:06:53,120
<i>But the truth is</i>

168
00:06:53,121 --> 00:06:56,289
<i>the so-called asteroid debris</i>

169
00:06:56,290 --> 00:07:01,378
<i>is a UFO that crash-landed on Earth.</i>

170
00:07:01,379 --> 00:07:05,340
<i>XIN partnered up
with private space company Edison Core,</i>

171
00:07:05,341 --> 00:07:10,428
<i>and after retrieving the UFO,
we have been managing it independently.</i>

172
00:07:10,429 --> 00:07:13,140
<i>The massive data retrieved from the UFO</i>

173
00:07:13,141 --> 00:07:15,100
<i>transcends human scientific knowledge.</i>

174
00:07:15,101 --> 00:07:16,601
<i>If it is exposed,</i>

175
00:07:16,602 --> 00:07:23,024
<i>it could impact all fields greatly,
especially the military.</i>

176
00:07:23,025 --> 00:07:29,781
<i>So, the XIN's supreme council
decided to keep all the data confidential.</i>

177
00:07:29,782 --> 00:07:33,910
<i>It is being kept in the the Black Room,
headquarters' secret storage.</i>

178
00:07:33,911 --> 00:07:35,203
The Black Room?

179
00:07:35,204 --> 00:07:37,956
<i>The Black Room boasts top-level security.</i>

180
00:07:37,957 --> 00:07:41,710
<i>So, to access the data,
even authorized personnel</i>

181
00:07:41,711 --> 00:07:45,130
<i>must go through multiple
time-consuming procedures.</i>

182
00:07:45,131 --> 00:07:50,552
<i>But some members of the XIN
oppose the council's decision.</i>

183
00:07:50,553 --> 00:07:55,475
<i>They think the data should be used
to make changes to the world order.</i>

184
00:07:56,517 --> 00:08:00,645
<i>These members aim to take over
the supreme council,</i>

185
00:08:00,646 --> 00:08:02,564
<i>and they call themselves the NIX.</i>

186
00:08:02,565 --> 00:08:05,567
<i>In alliance with defense contractors
and private military firms,</i>

187
00:08:05,568 --> 00:08:08,278
<i>they are attacking XIN's branches
across the world</i>

188
00:08:08,279 --> 00:08:11,199
<i>with the objective of obtaining
the data in the Black Room.</i>

189
00:08:12,074 --> 00:08:15,452
<i>Access to the Black Room
is severely restricted.</i>

190
00:08:15,453 --> 00:08:17,329
<i>But from 12:00 p.m. today,</i>

191
00:08:17,330 --> 00:08:19,789
<i>Agents Lee Yong-jin, John Park, Gabee,</i>

192
00:08:19,790 --> 00:08:22,584
<i>Hye-ri, Kim Do-hoon, and Karina</i>

193
00:08:22,585 --> 00:08:24,961
<i>have been granted access
to the Black Room.</i>

194
00:08:24,962 --> 00:08:27,631
<i>- In case of emergency…</i>
- It's a lot of pressure.

195
00:08:27,632 --> 00:08:30,634
<i>…you must enter the Black Room
to access the data</i>

196
00:08:30,635 --> 00:08:31,594
<i>and delete all the files.</i>

197
00:08:32,345 --> 00:08:33,721
We need to delete them.

198
00:08:34,889 --> 00:08:38,433
<i>Here are the instructions
for accessing the Black Room data.</i>

199
00:08:38,434 --> 00:08:41,394
<i>The access granted--</i>

200
00:08:41,395 --> 00:08:42,522
What's going on?

201
00:08:43,439 --> 00:08:45,106
But we need that information.

202
00:08:45,107 --> 00:08:46,608
It's the most critical part.

203
00:08:46,609 --> 00:08:47,527
What happened?

204
00:09:14,971 --> 00:09:19,307
AGENTS OF MYSTERY SEASON 2

205
00:09:19,308 --> 00:09:20,518
What happened?

206
00:09:35,908 --> 00:09:39,412
UNKNOWN VEHICLE CRASHES INTO HQ

207
00:09:47,795 --> 00:09:49,129
- Someone's here.
- What on earth?

208
00:09:49,130 --> 00:09:50,589
- What is this?
- What's going on?

209
00:09:50,590 --> 00:09:52,800
Wait, hold on!

210
00:09:53,884 --> 00:09:57,429
- What's going on?
- Wait, hold up!

211
00:09:57,430 --> 00:09:58,638
ARMED SOLDIERS ENTER

212
00:09:58,639 --> 00:09:59,848
This is an emergency.

213
00:09:59,849 --> 00:10:02,392
There's a ticking time bomb in this base.

214
00:10:02,393 --> 00:10:04,769
You have to escape right now.

215
00:10:04,770 --> 00:10:06,229
- I'll repeat.
- You're on our side, right?

216
00:10:06,230 --> 00:10:08,064
There's a ticking time bomb in this base.

217
00:10:08,065 --> 00:10:10,150
You have to escape right now.

218
00:10:10,151 --> 00:10:12,319
- I don't think we should put these on.
- Please cooperate.

219
00:10:12,320 --> 00:10:13,571
I don't think we should wear these.

220
00:10:14,530 --> 00:10:15,447
We must escape.

221
00:10:15,448 --> 00:10:17,782
- Who are you?
- Okay, put it on.

222
00:10:17,783 --> 00:10:19,868
THEY GET CHOKERS INSTEAD OF ANSWERS

223
00:10:19,869 --> 00:10:21,203
There's no time.

224
00:10:22,163 --> 00:10:23,830
Are you NIX?

225
00:10:23,831 --> 00:10:25,249
Don't ask questions.

226
00:10:26,626 --> 00:10:27,876
WHAT DID HE SAY?

227
00:10:27,877 --> 00:10:29,170
We must escape right now.

228
00:10:30,963 --> 00:10:31,881
Please follow him.

229
00:10:32,798 --> 00:10:34,300
We must escape right now.

230
00:10:37,345 --> 00:10:39,387
Are we taking the car?

231
00:10:39,388 --> 00:10:41,056
This is…

232
00:10:41,057 --> 00:10:42,932
But the portal…

233
00:10:42,933 --> 00:10:45,310
- Get into the vehicle.
- We need to ride the portal.

234
00:10:45,311 --> 00:10:49,189
<i>Usually, the portal on the side opens.</i>

235
00:10:49,190 --> 00:10:53,151
We were supposed to transport in that.

236
00:10:53,152 --> 00:10:55,904
- We need to ride the portal.
- They're making us get on.

237
00:10:55,905 --> 00:10:57,572
GET IN THE CAR

238
00:10:57,573 --> 00:11:00,117
FORCED INTO THE VEHICLE
WITH NO CHANCE TO RESIST

239
00:11:00,826 --> 00:11:02,744
<i>It was scary.</i>

240
00:11:02,745 --> 00:11:06,498
I thought about all the insurance I had.

241
00:11:06,499 --> 00:11:09,000
- You must get into the vehicle now.
- Okay.

242
00:11:09,001 --> 00:11:10,168
You must get in right now.

243
00:11:10,169 --> 00:11:11,671
There's no time.

244
00:11:12,546 --> 00:11:15,090
<i>They didn't seem like allies.</i>

245
00:11:15,091 --> 00:11:17,467
It felt like we were being kidnapped.

246
00:11:17,468 --> 00:11:21,263
<i>We all got into the van
with the same doubt.</i>

247
00:11:26,477 --> 00:11:28,311
<i>I thought, "Now, we're getting started."</i>

248
00:11:28,312 --> 00:11:30,522
It felt very real. They've gone all out.

249
00:11:30,523 --> 00:11:33,066
The creators have really gone all out.

250
00:11:33,067 --> 00:11:35,319
I'm so shaken.

251
00:11:36,862 --> 00:11:38,363
Is this a real vehicle?

252
00:11:38,364 --> 00:11:39,531
Are we really moving?

253
00:11:39,532 --> 00:11:41,324
- We're really moving?
- Hang on.

254
00:11:41,325 --> 00:11:43,284
- It's really moving.
- Where are we going?

255
00:11:43,285 --> 00:11:44,536
I know where we are.

256
00:11:44,537 --> 00:11:47,288
- We've gone off-road.
- Have we?

257
00:11:47,289 --> 00:11:48,957
- This is mad.
- Are you serious?

258
00:11:48,958 --> 00:11:51,418
- I did not see this coming.
- I can't see anything.

259
00:11:51,419 --> 00:11:53,461
- This is insane.
- I can't see anything.

260
00:11:53,462 --> 00:11:55,171
Wherever we were going,

261
00:11:55,172 --> 00:11:59,551
<i>there were a lot of slopes,
and the van kept shaking.</i>

262
00:11:59,552 --> 00:12:01,428
That made me really nervous.

263
00:12:01,429 --> 00:12:03,888
I figured we were
heading somewhere unusual.

264
00:12:03,889 --> 00:12:07,392
<i>The van kept rocking,
and we could hear water sloshing.</i>

265
00:12:07,393 --> 00:12:09,144
<i>I pictured all kinds of scenarios.</i>

266
00:12:09,145 --> 00:12:11,438
- This is something else.
- What is this, anyway?

267
00:12:11,439 --> 00:12:12,355
Right?

268
00:12:12,356 --> 00:12:13,815
<i>They put a choker on us.</i>

269
00:12:13,816 --> 00:12:16,568
Would they do this
if they were on our side?

270
00:12:16,569 --> 00:12:17,944
The choker was suspicious.

271
00:12:17,945 --> 00:12:21,406
It felt like it could explode at any time.

272
00:12:21,407 --> 00:12:24,159
- This red light is making me nervous.
- Me too.

273
00:12:24,160 --> 00:12:27,328
It's like that movie <i>Kingsman.</i>

274
00:12:27,329 --> 00:12:28,496
Don't you think?

275
00:12:28,497 --> 00:12:31,124
I feel like it could explode.

276
00:12:31,125 --> 00:12:32,250
- And blow us up?
- Right.

277
00:12:32,251 --> 00:12:36,212
- We need to get to the Black Room…
- Delete the file.

278
00:12:36,213 --> 00:12:37,672
We need to delete the file.

279
00:12:37,673 --> 00:12:40,300
XIN is our ally.

280
00:12:40,301 --> 00:12:42,719
- NIX is the enemy.
- Right.

281
00:12:42,720 --> 00:12:44,471
<i>Before we could hear the instructions,</i>

282
00:12:44,472 --> 00:12:47,098
<i>-the screen cut out.
- It did.</i>

283
00:12:47,099 --> 00:12:48,892
<i>That's when they entered.</i>

284
00:12:48,893 --> 00:12:52,395
<i>Were they really on our side?</i>

285
00:12:52,396 --> 00:12:56,816
We gained permission
to enter from 12 p.m., right?

286
00:12:56,817 --> 00:12:58,443
<i>From 12 p.m. today,</i>

287
00:12:58,444 --> 00:13:01,070
<i>you have been granted access
to the Black Room.</i>

288
00:13:01,071 --> 00:13:03,490
- Maybe that's why they kidnapped us.
- Right.

289
00:13:03,491 --> 00:13:04,824
You could be right.

290
00:13:04,825 --> 00:13:05,867
If they were allies,

291
00:13:05,868 --> 00:13:08,870
- they'd have given us a heads-up.
- Right.

292
00:13:08,871 --> 00:13:11,748
- We've stopped.
- I'm nervous.

293
00:13:11,749 --> 00:13:13,459
- No, wait.
- We're really stopping?

294
00:13:14,084 --> 00:13:17,253
- Are they letting us out or not?
- Today's mission is scary.

295
00:13:17,254 --> 00:13:18,421
There's smoke coming in.

296
00:13:18,422 --> 00:13:19,672
You're kidding.

297
00:13:19,673 --> 00:13:21,008
Are they putting us to sleep?

298
00:13:25,054 --> 00:13:27,139
It's actually the fog.

299
00:13:29,475 --> 00:13:30,433
- What the heck?
- What?

300
00:13:30,434 --> 00:13:31,684
I'm really scared.

301
00:13:31,685 --> 00:13:33,811
What are they planning?

302
00:13:33,812 --> 00:13:35,313
My light's changing.

303
00:13:35,314 --> 00:13:38,316
- The choker changed color.
- It's green now.

304
00:13:38,317 --> 00:13:40,861
THE LIGHT HAS TURNED GREEN

305
00:13:42,947 --> 00:13:44,155
They're all green, right?

306
00:13:44,156 --> 00:13:45,199
- Yes.
- They are.

307
00:13:47,034 --> 00:13:49,870
AND THE DOOR OPENS

308
00:13:50,621 --> 00:13:52,747
- We saw this in the video.
- It's the Black Room.

309
00:13:52,748 --> 00:13:54,166
This is crazy.

310
00:13:58,087 --> 00:13:59,838
The door just opened? Wait.

311
00:14:00,589 --> 00:14:03,007
EVERYBODY GETS OUT

312
00:14:03,008 --> 00:14:05,218
- What's going on?
- This is so stressful.

313
00:14:05,219 --> 00:14:07,178
- Where are we?
- It seems like--

314
00:14:07,179 --> 00:14:08,930
- It's the Black Room.
- That's the way in.

315
00:14:08,931 --> 00:14:10,349
Today's mission…

316
00:14:13,644 --> 00:14:15,061
Let's go together.

317
00:14:15,062 --> 00:14:16,271
- I'm scared.
- Get back inside.

318
00:14:16,272 --> 00:14:17,398
The light's turning on.

319
00:14:21,944 --> 00:14:24,028
This stuff gives me the creeps.

320
00:14:24,029 --> 00:14:25,322
How many doors are there?

321
00:14:27,032 --> 00:14:29,367
<i>It was a white corridor with doors.</i>

322
00:14:29,368 --> 00:14:32,370
<i>One big door had a large zero on it.</i>

323
00:14:32,371 --> 00:14:36,207
It was like a corridor
from the movie <i>The Matrix.</i>

324
00:14:36,208 --> 00:14:38,585
<i>It was very surreal.</i>

325
00:14:38,586 --> 00:14:40,670
We need to open them all?

326
00:14:40,671 --> 00:14:43,549
We must get through them
in order to enter the Black Room.

327
00:14:44,758 --> 00:14:47,010
Isn't this based on that movie <i>Cube?</i>

328
00:14:47,011 --> 00:14:48,177
That's what it reminds me of.

329
00:14:48,178 --> 00:14:51,307
I felt overwhelmed.
I was braced for a wild ride.

330
00:14:52,016 --> 00:14:53,641
Let's move slowly.

331
00:14:53,642 --> 00:14:55,685
- What is all this?
- They're all locked.

332
00:14:55,686 --> 00:14:58,855
It's dangerous. You should go first, John.

333
00:14:58,856 --> 00:15:00,732
The door's closed.

334
00:15:00,733 --> 00:15:02,442
- There's something on every door.
- I get it.

335
00:15:02,443 --> 00:15:03,943
I think we must solve the puzzles

336
00:15:03,944 --> 00:15:06,654
- to get the passcodes.
- They're all numbers.

337
00:15:06,655 --> 00:15:08,865
- They're all…
- I don't feel up to this.

338
00:15:08,866 --> 00:15:10,617
This is crazy.

339
00:15:10,618 --> 00:15:13,661
There were too many doors to count.

340
00:15:13,662 --> 00:15:15,121
<i>And there were patterns</i>

341
00:15:15,122 --> 00:15:17,165
<i>that seemed like challenges
we had to solve.</i>

342
00:15:17,166 --> 00:15:19,834
This is how much solving

343
00:15:19,835 --> 00:15:22,253
- we need to do today, right?
- Right.

344
00:15:22,254 --> 00:15:23,672
<i>I was at a loss.</i>

345
00:15:24,590 --> 00:15:26,425
Let's look around first.

346
00:15:27,217 --> 00:15:29,302
JOHN MAKES HIS WAY TO THE END

347
00:15:29,303 --> 00:15:31,512
The end doors are 115 and 215.

348
00:15:31,513 --> 00:15:33,431
There are 15 doors on each side.

349
00:15:33,432 --> 00:15:34,850
30 ROOMS IN TOTAL

350
00:15:36,268 --> 00:15:37,602
- Gabee.
- Yes?

351
00:15:37,603 --> 00:15:39,145
Brace yourself, seriously.

352
00:15:39,146 --> 00:15:41,230
I seriously can't believe this.

353
00:15:41,231 --> 00:15:42,357
I love this.

354
00:15:42,358 --> 00:15:43,608
RIDDLES ARE MY THING

355
00:15:43,609 --> 00:15:45,068
- I'm so excited.
- You handle it.

356
00:15:45,069 --> 00:15:47,987
Everyone else was a bit worried.

357
00:15:47,988 --> 00:15:49,781
But I was bursting with excitement.

358
00:15:49,782 --> 00:15:52,575
- This isn't an escape room.
- This is the Log-in Room.

359
00:15:52,576 --> 00:15:56,788
One room had a "Log-in" sign.

360
00:15:56,789 --> 00:15:58,790
Does it mean we have to do this first?

361
00:15:58,791 --> 00:16:00,501
- Maybe.
- You might be right.

362
00:16:02,503 --> 00:16:06,172
- Oh, my!
- That scared me!

363
00:16:06,173 --> 00:16:08,049
- Did it open?
- Yes, it's open.

364
00:16:08,050 --> 00:16:09,550
- It feels like an invite.
- Did you open it?

365
00:16:09,551 --> 00:16:10,844
It just opened.

366
00:16:13,514 --> 00:16:17,225
- It looks like an office.
- This must be the main room.

367
00:16:17,226 --> 00:16:18,226
Let's go in.

368
00:16:18,227 --> 00:16:19,727
- Let's log in first.
- Go on in.

369
00:16:19,728 --> 00:16:23,482
LOG-IN ROOM

370
00:16:24,191 --> 00:16:27,485
It seems like we can move freely in here.

371
00:16:27,486 --> 00:16:28,736
It seems that way.

372
00:16:28,737 --> 00:16:29,780
Look here.

373
00:16:30,948 --> 00:16:32,281
RATTLE

374
00:16:32,282 --> 00:16:33,908
Are there things we need to open?

375
00:16:33,909 --> 00:16:34,910
It's locked.

376
00:16:35,494 --> 00:16:36,995
Should we close the door?

377
00:16:36,996 --> 00:16:39,248
DOOR CLOSED

378
00:16:48,924 --> 00:16:53,302
The corridor reminds me
of the Everland horror maze.

379
00:16:53,303 --> 00:16:55,847
<i>Welcome to the Log-in Room.</i>

380
00:16:55,848 --> 00:16:58,100
A STRANGE VOICE IS SUDDENLY HEARD

381
00:17:00,686 --> 00:17:04,355
<i>I'm your login assistant, Oracle.</i>

382
00:17:04,356 --> 00:17:05,481
- Oracle?
- Oracle.

383
00:17:05,482 --> 00:17:09,737
<i>The Black Room can only be accessed
by agents who successfully log in.</i>

384
00:17:10,446 --> 00:17:14,949
<i>Anyone who wishes to log in
must each say their name.</i>

385
00:17:14,950 --> 00:17:16,492
- Our names?
- Our names?

386
00:17:16,493 --> 00:17:17,870
WHY EACH OF US?

387
00:17:19,496 --> 00:17:21,080
Would you like to go first, Yong-jin?

388
00:17:21,081 --> 00:17:22,457
THE COURTEOUS YOUNGEST MEMBER

389
00:17:22,458 --> 00:17:24,084
John Park.

390
00:17:26,795 --> 00:17:28,046
What's with this guy?

391
00:17:28,047 --> 00:17:31,008
- You're meant to say your own name.
- I was just being considerate.

392
00:17:31,592 --> 00:17:33,176
You're supposed to lead us.

393
00:17:33,177 --> 00:17:34,969
- He was just experimenting.
- Okay.

394
00:17:34,970 --> 00:17:36,387
- Behold!
- Behold.

395
00:17:36,388 --> 00:17:37,681
SUMMONING AI FROM SEASON 1

396
00:17:38,390 --> 00:17:39,349
Lee Yong-jin.

397
00:17:40,392 --> 00:17:42,061
LOGIN ATTEMPT AS INSTRUCTED

398
00:17:42,770 --> 00:17:44,855
- You're brave.
- Lee Yong-jin!

399
00:17:46,857 --> 00:17:48,858
- Do we need to step forward?
- Kim Do-hoon.

400
00:17:48,859 --> 00:17:51,069
SILENCE

401
00:17:51,070 --> 00:17:52,988
- Do we all need to try it?
- What do we do?

402
00:17:53,989 --> 00:17:55,657
- Should we all try?
- Yeah.

403
00:17:56,825 --> 00:17:58,327
Gabee.

404
00:18:00,329 --> 00:18:01,330
Karina.

405
00:18:04,124 --> 00:18:05,333
John Park.

406
00:18:05,334 --> 00:18:06,959
Are we doing this correctly?

407
00:18:06,960 --> 00:18:08,796
THE LAST ONE IS STILL DOUBTFUL

408
00:18:09,922 --> 00:18:12,340
- Hye-ri.
- Okay, it should work.

409
00:18:12,341 --> 00:18:14,258
<i>The agents who wish to log in</i>

410
00:18:14,259 --> 00:18:15,635
<i>- are Lee Yong-jin…</i>
- Yes.

411
00:18:15,636 --> 00:18:17,845
<i>…John Park, Gabee,</i>

412
00:18:17,846 --> 00:18:21,724
<i>Hye-ri, Kim Do-hoon, and Karina.</i>

413
00:18:21,725 --> 00:18:26,104
<i>You are all confirmed agents
of the XIN Seoul Division.</i>

414
00:18:26,105 --> 00:18:27,021
<i>Is that correct?</i>

415
00:18:27,022 --> 00:18:28,689
- Yes.
- Yes, that's right.

416
00:18:28,690 --> 00:18:30,858
- We're so cool.
<i>- Thank you for confirming.</i>

417
00:18:30,859 --> 00:18:32,568
- We're awesome.
- Seoul Division.

418
00:18:32,569 --> 00:18:36,739
<i>To verify your identities,
I will now run a body scan.</i>

419
00:18:36,740 --> 00:18:38,032
- What?
- What?

420
00:18:38,033 --> 00:18:39,951
<i>Please copy the pose</i>

421
00:18:39,952 --> 00:18:42,203
<i>-that is shown on the screen.</i>
- What?

422
00:18:42,204 --> 00:18:43,329
This is awkward.

423
00:18:43,330 --> 00:18:44,747
What kind of pose?

424
00:18:44,748 --> 00:18:46,791
THIS POSE

425
00:18:46,792 --> 00:18:48,209
YOU MUST BE KIDDING

426
00:18:48,210 --> 00:18:50,086
Hey, Oracle!

427
00:18:50,087 --> 00:18:51,212
This isn't right.

428
00:18:51,213 --> 00:18:53,089
- This is how we begin?
- You're kidding.

429
00:18:53,090 --> 00:18:56,551
Are they going for comedy this season?

430
00:18:56,552 --> 00:18:58,427
Do-hoon, you stand in the center.

431
00:18:58,428 --> 00:18:59,345
COPY THAT

432
00:18:59,346 --> 00:19:00,304
Can I stand?

433
00:19:00,305 --> 00:19:02,598
Do I grab you?
Oh, they're linked like this.

434
00:19:02,599 --> 00:19:03,933
- You and I kneel here.
- Right.

435
00:19:03,934 --> 00:19:04,892
We stand like this.

436
00:19:04,893 --> 00:19:07,270
We're at the bottom.

437
00:19:07,271 --> 00:19:08,604
- Like this?
- My arm goes up here.

438
00:19:08,605 --> 00:19:09,772
Who do I grab?

439
00:19:09,773 --> 00:19:11,023
- John, grab me.
- It has to go back.

440
00:19:11,024 --> 00:19:13,109
Your arm goes around our shoulders.

441
00:19:13,110 --> 00:19:15,319
Then, I have to grab Yong-jin's hand.

442
00:19:15,320 --> 00:19:16,904
- Right, like this.
- I grab Karina's hand.

443
00:19:16,905 --> 00:19:18,823
Gabee, you need to grab Hye-ri's hand.

444
00:19:18,824 --> 00:19:22,869
<i>Please move back.
All of your bodies must be visible.</i>

445
00:19:22,870 --> 00:19:24,371
- Move back.
- Okay.

446
00:19:24,997 --> 00:19:26,122
THEY FOLLOW INSTRUCTIONS WELL

447
00:19:26,123 --> 00:19:27,165
- We're so cute.
- This is it.

448
00:19:27,166 --> 00:19:28,958
TA-DA

449
00:19:28,959 --> 00:19:32,128
- Is this right?
- Yes, isn't it?

450
00:19:32,129 --> 00:19:34,213
Wait, I don't think so.

451
00:19:34,214 --> 00:19:35,381
This should go…

452
00:19:35,382 --> 00:19:37,049
- No, it's correct.
- It's right.

453
00:19:37,050 --> 00:19:38,009
Shift a little.

454
00:19:38,010 --> 00:19:38,926
What do you think?

455
00:19:38,927 --> 00:19:40,928
- Form a triangle.
- Impressive, right?

456
00:19:40,929 --> 00:19:42,139
What do you think?

457
00:19:45,309 --> 00:19:47,059
Do our hands need to be visible?

458
00:19:47,060 --> 00:19:49,437
<i>Please check that your hands
are positioned correctly.</i>

459
00:19:49,438 --> 00:19:50,479
- Move yours forward.
- Wait.

460
00:19:50,480 --> 00:19:51,939
Do-hoon has to be in the front.

461
00:19:51,940 --> 00:19:53,691
- Like this?
- That's it.

462
00:19:53,692 --> 00:19:55,776
- My hand needs to be out front.
- Okay.

463
00:19:55,777 --> 00:19:57,486
- Mine has to go back.
- I got it.

464
00:19:57,487 --> 00:19:59,615
The arm has to be on the inside.

465
00:20:00,532 --> 00:20:01,532
There we go.

466
00:20:01,533 --> 00:20:02,658
Are you satisfied?

467
00:20:02,659 --> 00:20:04,286
Let's smile. One, two, three.

468
00:20:05,037 --> 00:20:06,454
2ND ATTEMPT WITH A SMILE

469
00:20:06,455 --> 00:20:07,872
- Is this it?
- Are we good?

470
00:20:07,873 --> 00:20:10,082
<i>The scan will begin.</i>

471
00:20:10,083 --> 00:20:11,000
Please hurry.

472
00:20:11,001 --> 00:20:11,960
SCANNING STARTS

473
00:20:13,754 --> 00:20:16,047
I'm not sure this scan is a good thing.

474
00:20:16,048 --> 00:20:17,215
Shall we smile?

475
00:20:17,216 --> 00:20:19,133
SMILES

476
00:20:19,134 --> 00:20:20,384
I bet the AI is smiling too.

477
00:20:20,385 --> 00:20:21,636
EVERYONE SMILE

478
00:20:21,637 --> 00:20:22,720
FINGERS CROSSED

479
00:20:22,721 --> 00:20:24,430
Make sure your feet are in position.

480
00:20:24,431 --> 00:20:25,556
- It's done.
- It's finished.

481
00:20:25,557 --> 00:20:27,516
<i>Verification complete.</i>

482
00:20:27,517 --> 00:20:29,018
We got it right.

483
00:20:29,019 --> 00:20:30,562
- Did we do it?
- It's hot.

484
00:20:31,230 --> 00:20:33,189
- This got me worked up.
<i>- From the start,</i>

485
00:20:33,190 --> 00:20:35,442
everything fell into place.

486
00:20:36,151 --> 00:20:38,612
<i>We quickly got the pose right to log in.</i>

487
00:20:40,489 --> 00:20:44,492
<i>These are the guidelines
for entering the Black Room.</i>

488
00:20:44,493 --> 00:20:45,701
Okay, the guidelines.

489
00:20:45,702 --> 00:20:50,289
<i>To access the data
that is contained in the Black Room,</i>

490
00:20:50,290 --> 00:20:54,877
<i>you must go through 11 security checks
in chronological order.</i>

491
00:20:54,878 --> 00:20:56,420
We need to go in order.

492
00:20:56,421 --> 00:20:59,131
<i>As part of the security procedures,</i>

493
00:20:59,132 --> 00:21:01,467
<i>the system is protected
by defense barriers.</i>

494
00:21:01,468 --> 00:21:03,636
<i>To get through the security checks,</i>

495
00:21:03,637 --> 00:21:07,265
<i>you need key cards to unlock each barrier.</i>

496
00:21:07,266 --> 00:21:09,183
- A key card?
<i>- Using the key card,</i>

497
00:21:09,184 --> 00:21:11,394
<i>you must deactivate the defense barriers.</i>

498
00:21:11,395 --> 00:21:14,355
<i>Every time you pass a security check,</i>

499
00:21:14,356 --> 00:21:17,276
<i>you will get a new key card
for the next stage.</i>

500
00:21:17,901 --> 00:21:21,363
<i>The first key card
will be issued in this room.</i>

501
00:21:23,573 --> 00:21:25,741
- Awesome.
- They're giving it to us this easily?

502
00:21:25,742 --> 00:21:27,702
<i>There was a room number on the key card.</i>

503
00:21:27,703 --> 00:21:31,330
We had to enter the room to do a mission.

504
00:21:31,331 --> 00:21:33,958
<i>Then, we could move on to the next room.</i>

505
00:21:33,959 --> 00:21:38,045
Eventually, we would end up
at the Black Room.

506
00:21:38,046 --> 00:21:39,839
It could be an alien lifeform

507
00:21:39,840 --> 00:21:43,384
<i>or some new technology
that was discovered on the UFO.</i>

508
00:21:43,385 --> 00:21:44,635
We couldn't be sure.

509
00:21:44,636 --> 00:21:47,555
<i>But something important was in that room.</i>

510
00:21:47,556 --> 00:21:50,726
And we had to get to it before NIX.

511
00:21:53,103 --> 00:21:56,314
- This--
<i>- If you run into trouble at any stage,</i>

512
00:21:56,315 --> 00:21:58,232
<i>press the F1 key.</i>

513
00:21:58,233 --> 00:21:59,734
- F1?
<i>- I will assist you.</i>

514
00:21:59,735 --> 00:22:00,735
- Which button?
- F1?

515
00:22:00,736 --> 00:22:04,071
<i>But you must use the F1 key carefully.</i>

516
00:22:04,072 --> 00:22:05,614
- I see.
- Why?

517
00:22:05,615 --> 00:22:07,451
ORACLE TERMINATED WITH A WARNING

518
00:22:09,828 --> 00:22:14,373
- What was that?
- Why should we be careful with the F1 key?

519
00:22:14,374 --> 00:22:16,334
Is it like a reset button?

520
00:22:16,335 --> 00:22:17,626
I think it's for gaining clues.

521
00:22:17,627 --> 00:22:20,796
- I think we need…
- Should we go to room 205?

522
00:22:20,797 --> 00:22:23,758
-…to solve this to get to the next room.
- Right.

523
00:22:23,759 --> 00:22:25,469
So, let's go to room 205.

524
00:22:26,178 --> 00:22:27,471
Let's go.

525
00:22:29,306 --> 00:22:30,806
Go on ahead. We'll look around.

526
00:22:30,807 --> 00:22:31,641
- All right.
- Okay.

527
00:22:32,851 --> 00:22:34,227
Room 205?

528
00:22:35,353 --> 00:22:37,229
I think we need to make it match.

529
00:22:37,230 --> 00:22:38,482
Right, like this…

530
00:22:42,611 --> 00:22:45,571
ROOM 205 PUZZLE IS FULL OF NUMBERS

531
00:22:45,572 --> 00:22:48,491
AND ROOM 205 KEY CARD

532
00:22:48,492 --> 00:22:50,076
JUMPING INTO PROBLEM-SOLVING

533
00:22:50,077 --> 00:22:50,911
Here?

534
00:22:56,291 --> 00:22:59,001
FOCUSED

535
00:22:59,002 --> 00:23:01,504
Oracle, can you answer us?

536
00:23:01,505 --> 00:23:02,588
NO REPLY

537
00:23:02,589 --> 00:23:03,673
I guess not.

538
00:23:04,633 --> 00:23:05,675
She's not answering.

539
00:23:06,343 --> 00:23:08,344
DO-HOON FIDGETING AROUND

540
00:23:08,345 --> 00:23:12,556
The carpet under our feet got me thinking.

541
00:23:12,557 --> 00:23:15,476
This pose could be a trap,
and the floor could open.

542
00:23:15,477 --> 00:23:17,561
I feared what was under the carpet.

543
00:23:17,562 --> 00:23:19,064
- Should we all try?
- Yes.

544
00:23:20,232 --> 00:23:21,899
NERVOUS FLINCHING

545
00:23:21,900 --> 00:23:23,526
I thought there might be something.

546
00:23:23,527 --> 00:23:25,027
<i>- So, I checked under it.</i>
- There's nothing.

547
00:23:25,028 --> 00:23:26,320
Should we take a look?

548
00:23:26,321 --> 00:23:28,030
How about under the carpet?

549
00:23:28,031 --> 00:23:29,365
There's nothing, right?

550
00:23:29,366 --> 00:23:30,534
There's nothing.

551
00:23:31,159 --> 00:23:32,994
Luckily, there wasn't anything.

552
00:23:33,995 --> 00:23:37,165
THE KEY CARD TEAM IS STILL WORKING ON IT

553
00:23:37,874 --> 00:23:41,377
- Since some numbers are bigger…
- Right.

554
00:23:41,378 --> 00:23:43,045
…I think the sizes should match.

555
00:23:43,046 --> 00:23:44,088
USE THE SIZE TO SOLVE

556
00:23:44,089 --> 00:23:45,798
- You're right.
- That's so clever.

557
00:23:45,799 --> 00:23:47,133
This isn't it.

558
00:23:47,134 --> 00:23:48,552
That's not it either.

559
00:23:52,639 --> 00:23:55,307
If you look at the margin, that's a six.

560
00:23:55,308 --> 00:23:57,726
Let's focus on that six
to make things easier.

561
00:23:57,727 --> 00:23:59,145
A six that looks like this.

562
00:23:59,146 --> 00:24:03,023
We picked a number that stood out

563
00:24:03,024 --> 00:24:05,943
and used it as a frame of reference.

564
00:24:05,944 --> 00:24:07,403
WHICH OF THESE SIXES IS IT?

565
00:24:07,404 --> 00:24:08,238
Could it be this?

566
00:24:09,990 --> 00:24:12,868
But it looks a bit slanted.

567
00:24:13,618 --> 00:24:14,703
Here.

568
00:24:15,495 --> 00:24:17,746
IS THIS THE ONE?

569
00:24:17,747 --> 00:24:19,583
It could be like this.

570
00:24:20,667 --> 00:24:22,877
It is!

571
00:24:22,878 --> 00:24:25,045
ONCE THE CARD IS ROTATED

572
00:24:25,046 --> 00:24:26,422
THE NUMBERS STAND OUT

573
00:24:26,423 --> 00:24:28,550
It's 5535.

574
00:24:29,968 --> 00:24:31,719
- It's 5535?
- Should we try it?

575
00:24:31,720 --> 00:24:33,012
You solved it already?

576
00:24:33,013 --> 00:24:34,388
That was fast.

577
00:24:34,389 --> 00:24:35,681
It's supposed to match?

578
00:24:35,682 --> 00:24:37,725
ENTERS 5535

579
00:24:37,726 --> 00:24:38,685
It opened.

580
00:24:39,936 --> 00:24:40,853
Let's go in.

581
00:24:40,854 --> 00:24:43,105
- I'm going to open it.
- Okay.

582
00:24:43,106 --> 00:24:44,107
OPENS ROOM 205

583
00:24:45,692 --> 00:24:47,151
Check it out.

584
00:24:47,152 --> 00:24:48,527
- What is this place?
- This is awesome!

585
00:24:48,528 --> 00:24:51,114
WHAT IS THIS PLACE THAT BRINGS EXCITEMENT?

586
00:24:52,157 --> 00:24:56,160
Q-01
BLACK ROOM

587
00:24:56,161 --> 00:25:00,956
<i>There were so many mirrors
that it was disorienting.</i>

588
00:25:00,957 --> 00:25:05,336
<i>Everything was shaped like a cube.</i>

589
00:25:05,337 --> 00:25:09,632
It made me realize
we were in the Black Room.

590
00:25:09,633 --> 00:25:11,884
WHAT'S THE FIRST SECRET OF THE BLACK ROOM?

591
00:25:11,885 --> 00:25:14,220
What? There's a toilet here.

592
00:25:14,221 --> 00:25:16,347
<i>There was a random toilet.</i>

593
00:25:16,348 --> 00:25:22,144
It was an airplane-style toilet seat
with a strong vacuum.

594
00:25:22,145 --> 00:25:23,604
ALL EYES ON THE RANDOM TOILET

595
00:25:23,605 --> 00:25:24,647
- There's nothing.
- A toilet?

596
00:25:24,648 --> 00:25:27,191
A toilet? Is it a porta-potty?

597
00:25:27,192 --> 00:25:28,693
It's the kind you find on planes.

598
00:25:30,403 --> 00:25:31,612
What on earth?

599
00:25:31,613 --> 00:25:33,489
Let's not push it.

600
00:25:33,490 --> 00:25:36,158
<i>The toilet was the only thing there.</i>

601
00:25:36,159 --> 00:25:39,328
<i>So, I had no idea
what we were supposed to do.</i>

602
00:25:39,329 --> 00:25:41,372
<i>I was dumbfounded.</i>

603
00:25:41,373 --> 00:25:42,831
<i>What could it be for?</i>

604
00:25:42,832 --> 00:25:46,543
I thought it could mean
we had to stay in there for a while.

605
00:25:46,544 --> 00:25:47,753
It's the F1 key.

606
00:25:47,754 --> 00:25:48,837
The F1 key is here.

607
00:25:48,838 --> 00:25:50,214
- It's the F1 key.
- Yeah.

608
00:25:50,215 --> 00:25:51,674
Don't press it.

609
00:25:51,675 --> 00:25:54,385
I won't, but since it's right there…

610
00:25:54,386 --> 00:25:57,222
- Don't you want to press it?
- Yes, it's so tempting.

611
00:25:58,014 --> 00:26:00,600
- Oh, my!
- What is this?

612
00:26:01,309 --> 00:26:02,309
What is it?

613
00:26:02,310 --> 00:26:06,230
<i>Two ping pong balls
fell down from the ceiling.</i>

614
00:26:06,231 --> 00:26:09,316
<i>I was confused by their purpose.</i>

615
00:26:09,317 --> 00:26:11,944
- There are two balls.
- What are they for?

616
00:26:11,945 --> 00:26:14,029
- Do we put them in here?
- In here?

617
00:26:14,030 --> 00:26:16,532
Let's put one in for now.

618
00:26:16,533 --> 00:26:18,325
- Are we supposed to do this?
- Yes.

619
00:26:18,326 --> 00:26:19,410
"Push"?

620
00:26:19,411 --> 00:26:21,829
- Can we try just the button first?
- Okay.

621
00:26:21,830 --> 00:26:23,080
- Sounds good.
- Good idea.

622
00:26:23,081 --> 00:26:23,998
TRYING THE BUTTON WITHOUT BALLS

623
00:26:23,999 --> 00:26:25,542
- I'll press it.
- Go on.

624
00:26:27,585 --> 00:26:30,421
It's just a typical airplane toilet.

625
00:26:30,422 --> 00:26:32,214
Maybe we should put the balls in.

626
00:26:32,215 --> 00:26:34,466
There doesn't seem to be anything else.

627
00:26:34,467 --> 00:26:36,135
It's just so random.

628
00:26:36,136 --> 00:26:38,137
I feel so clueless.

629
00:26:38,138 --> 00:26:40,347
Seriously. What are we meant to solve?

630
00:26:40,348 --> 00:26:41,974
- It's locked.
- I figured.

631
00:26:41,975 --> 00:26:43,143
What is this?

632
00:26:44,394 --> 00:26:45,728
What could this be?

633
00:26:45,729 --> 00:26:49,815
<i>There was a monitor with "Q-01."</i>

634
00:26:49,816 --> 00:26:52,359
I thought the Q might stand for "quiz."

635
00:26:52,360 --> 00:26:56,656
I think it means "Quiz number one."

636
00:26:57,282 --> 00:27:00,659
- If we put the ball in there…
- The ball?

637
00:27:00,660 --> 00:27:02,411
…something might happen.

638
00:27:02,412 --> 00:27:03,662
- Should we try?
- Let's try it.

639
00:27:03,663 --> 00:27:05,122
It's our only choice.

640
00:27:05,123 --> 00:27:07,458
<i>There were ping pong balls and a toilet.</i>

641
00:27:07,459 --> 00:27:11,211
The balls were all we could flush.

642
00:27:11,212 --> 00:27:13,130
So, we tried it first.

643
00:27:13,131 --> 00:27:14,757
- Just put one in.
- Just one.

644
00:27:14,758 --> 00:27:16,925
1 BALL OUT

645
00:27:16,926 --> 00:27:20,889
ONE BALL FLUSHED

646
00:27:21,473 --> 00:27:22,890
It went in.

647
00:27:22,891 --> 00:27:25,017
Maybe it functions like a coin--

648
00:27:25,018 --> 00:27:26,019
What is that?

649
00:27:26,978 --> 00:27:28,479
BALLS TUMBLED DOWN FROM ABOVE

650
00:27:28,480 --> 00:27:29,938
- What is this?
- I see.

651
00:27:29,939 --> 00:27:31,899
There are so many.

652
00:27:31,900 --> 00:27:33,567
We flushed one, and now there are…

653
00:27:33,568 --> 00:27:35,277
One, two, three, four, five, six, seven.

654
00:27:35,278 --> 00:27:36,820
There are seven.

655
00:27:36,821 --> 00:27:39,239
Is there some kind of formula?

656
00:27:39,240 --> 00:27:41,492
- How many came out?
- Seven.

657
00:27:41,493 --> 00:27:43,077
There might be a formula.

658
00:27:43,078 --> 00:27:45,746
We flushed one, and seven came out.

659
00:27:45,747 --> 00:27:46,705
Seven.

660
00:27:46,706 --> 00:27:48,082
Let's flush another one.

661
00:27:48,083 --> 00:27:49,667
- Just one?
- Yes.

662
00:27:50,293 --> 00:27:52,878
- If it happens again, there's a formula.
- Right.

663
00:27:52,879 --> 00:27:54,171
I'll drop it in.

664
00:27:54,172 --> 00:27:57,591
1 BALL OUT AGAIN

665
00:27:57,592 --> 00:27:59,802
- What if they just keep falling?
- One, two, three…

666
00:27:59,803 --> 00:28:01,804
- There are seven.
- It's a formula.

667
00:28:01,805 --> 00:28:03,180
There's a formula.

668
00:28:03,181 --> 00:28:04,724
Flush one, get seven.

669
00:28:05,350 --> 00:28:06,892
- Should we put two in?
- Yeah.

670
00:28:06,893 --> 00:28:09,270
- Should we try?
- Yes, let's test it out.

671
00:28:10,105 --> 00:28:11,563
Something might happen.

672
00:28:11,564 --> 00:28:13,191
- Let's try two.
- Flush two.

673
00:28:14,442 --> 00:28:15,401
JUMPSCARE

674
00:28:15,402 --> 00:28:16,611
That scared me.

675
00:28:18,071 --> 00:28:19,947
One, two, three, four…

676
00:28:19,948 --> 00:28:21,782
- There are four.
- Four?

677
00:28:21,783 --> 00:28:23,367
- Flush two, get four?
- Why four?

678
00:28:23,368 --> 00:28:24,952
- How does it work?
- It's a formula.

679
00:28:24,953 --> 00:28:26,579
- Should we try three?
- Yes.

680
00:28:27,205 --> 00:28:28,372
I'll flush three.

681
00:28:28,373 --> 00:28:31,667
3 BALLS OUT

682
00:28:31,668 --> 00:28:33,545
I can't figure it out.

683
00:28:35,463 --> 00:28:37,047
We got one.

684
00:28:37,048 --> 00:28:38,590
Did we get seven when we flushed one?

685
00:28:38,591 --> 00:28:40,217
We got seven for one,

686
00:28:40,218 --> 00:28:42,928
four for two, and one for three.

687
00:28:42,929 --> 00:28:47,391
To figure out the formula,
we needed lots of examples.

688
00:28:47,392 --> 00:28:48,476
So, we tried every possibility.

689
00:28:49,269 --> 00:28:50,894
- We put four in.
- We flushed four.

690
00:28:50,895 --> 00:28:53,230
4 BALLS OUT

691
00:28:53,231 --> 00:28:55,858
WITH 4 BALLS, A BUNCH TUMBLE OUT

692
00:28:55,859 --> 00:28:57,735
Why are there so many?

693
00:28:57,736 --> 00:28:59,737
- Is it eight?
- One, two, three, four…

694
00:28:59,738 --> 00:29:00,655
- Eight.
- There are eight.

695
00:29:01,322 --> 00:29:02,240
Let's try five.

696
00:29:05,201 --> 00:29:06,493
We got five more.

697
00:29:06,494 --> 00:29:07,703
Five results in five more?

698
00:29:07,704 --> 00:29:11,290
6 BALLS OUT

699
00:29:11,291 --> 00:29:12,833
- We've got two.
- Two?

700
00:29:12,834 --> 00:29:14,042
We put in six and got two.

701
00:29:14,043 --> 00:29:15,878
Is there a formula here?

702
00:29:15,879 --> 00:29:16,796
I can't see one.

703
00:29:17,881 --> 00:29:19,174
We've lost one bar.

704
00:29:19,799 --> 00:29:21,091
GAUGE DOWN BY ONE BAR

705
00:29:21,092 --> 00:29:22,593
Wait, hold up.

706
00:29:22,594 --> 00:29:25,345
- We've seen these colors before.
- Right.

707
00:29:25,346 --> 00:29:27,848
- You're right.
- Right? They match our choker lights.

708
00:29:27,849 --> 00:29:29,808
Will these explode when the batteries die?

709
00:29:29,809 --> 00:29:31,143
THEY WILL EXPLODE?

710
00:29:31,144 --> 00:29:32,186
That must be it.

711
00:29:32,187 --> 00:29:34,855
<i>If the bar runs out, are we done for?</i>

712
00:29:34,856 --> 00:29:37,441
We suddenly felt pressed for time.

713
00:29:37,442 --> 00:29:40,569
- The first room's already challenging.
- Seriously.

714
00:29:40,570 --> 00:29:44,656
Since we can see our reflection,

715
00:29:44,657 --> 00:29:47,951
maybe we ourselves are the clue?

716
00:29:47,952 --> 00:29:49,953
A REASONABLE GUESS

717
00:29:49,954 --> 00:29:51,705
But I have no idea what it could be.

718
00:29:51,706 --> 00:29:54,834
F1 KEY

719
00:29:55,668 --> 00:29:57,127
I want to press it.

720
00:29:57,128 --> 00:29:59,004
It said we had to be careful.

721
00:29:59,005 --> 00:30:01,673
What if it drains our lifeline?

722
00:30:01,674 --> 00:30:03,342
THERE'S A POSSIBILITY

723
00:30:03,343 --> 00:30:07,888
I thought if we were really stuck,
we should use it only as our last resort.

724
00:30:07,889 --> 00:30:09,974
What could it be?

725
00:30:11,601 --> 00:30:15,438
Gabee really doesn't lie.

726
00:30:16,064 --> 00:30:17,731
You said you weren't good at this.

727
00:30:17,732 --> 00:30:19,900
A SUCKER PUNCH FOR THE NEWEST AGENT

728
00:30:19,901 --> 00:30:23,028
- You really meant it.
- You've done this before.

729
00:30:23,029 --> 00:30:24,822
Don't take it the wrong way.

730
00:30:24,823 --> 00:30:26,406
None of us has solved anything.

731
00:30:26,407 --> 00:30:28,534
- You're being unwelcoming.
- Don't take it the wrong way.

732
00:30:28,535 --> 00:30:30,869
I really want to solve something.

733
00:30:30,870 --> 00:30:32,913
- We all feel that way, right?
- What could it be?

734
00:30:32,914 --> 00:30:36,250
DETERMINED AGENT KARINA

735
00:30:36,251 --> 00:30:38,544
I'll secure a few more for now.

736
00:30:38,545 --> 00:30:39,795
That's one.

737
00:30:39,796 --> 00:30:40,921
1 BALL OUT TO EARN EXTRA

738
00:30:40,922 --> 00:30:42,756
Luckily, we won't ever run out of balls.

739
00:30:42,757 --> 00:30:44,591
1 BALL OUT, 7 BALLS IN

740
00:30:44,592 --> 00:30:46,343
I really want to solve this.

741
00:30:46,344 --> 00:30:49,388
<i>The amount we got varied a lot
depending on the number we put in.</i>

742
00:30:49,389 --> 00:30:53,559
We thought we needed to flush
at least ten to find a pattern.

743
00:30:53,560 --> 00:30:55,018
Let's flush ten.

744
00:30:55,019 --> 00:30:57,688
- Ten?
- Yes, we haven't tried that yet.

745
00:30:57,689 --> 00:31:01,066
10 BALLS OUT

746
00:31:01,067 --> 00:31:02,776
We need to find and solve the formula.

747
00:31:02,777 --> 00:31:04,444
- Right.
- There must be one.

748
00:31:04,445 --> 00:31:06,572
SILENCE

749
00:31:06,573 --> 00:31:08,074
- Did you flush ten?
- I did.

750
00:31:09,450 --> 00:31:10,367
NONE CAME OUT?

751
00:31:10,368 --> 00:31:11,285
Ten balls…

752
00:31:11,286 --> 00:31:12,578
- Look at that.
- No way.

753
00:31:12,579 --> 00:31:15,372
We flushed ten and got zero back.

754
00:31:15,373 --> 00:31:16,833
That could be a clue.

755
00:31:18,042 --> 00:31:21,044
If you look at the monitor's reflection,

756
00:31:21,045 --> 00:31:22,922
it looks like 10-Q.

757
00:31:24,173 --> 00:31:25,257
WHAT?

758
00:31:25,258 --> 00:31:26,842
Ten minus zero?

759
00:31:26,843 --> 00:31:29,803
Is that it? Ten minus zero?

760
00:31:29,804 --> 00:31:31,054
- Could it be that?
- I think so.

761
00:31:31,055 --> 00:31:34,558
- I can see it.
- But I can't figure out the next part.

762
00:31:34,559 --> 00:31:36,476
You can do it. Try it.

763
00:31:36,477 --> 00:31:37,895
Go on.

764
00:31:37,896 --> 00:31:38,979
Try what?

765
00:31:38,980 --> 00:31:41,149
GABEE, YOU WERE SO CLOSE

766
00:31:42,066 --> 00:31:43,401
What should she try?

767
00:31:44,319 --> 00:31:46,445
FEELING SHEEPISH

768
00:31:46,446 --> 00:31:48,739
Ten minus zero? Ten minus Q?

769
00:31:48,740 --> 00:31:50,240
What could it be?

770
00:31:50,241 --> 00:31:51,533
Maybe we should press F1.

771
00:31:51,534 --> 00:31:52,910
We've lost two bars.

772
00:31:52,911 --> 00:31:55,203
- We're still on the first challenge.
- I know, right?

773
00:31:55,204 --> 00:31:56,330
GAUGE DOWN BY 2 BARS

774
00:31:56,331 --> 00:31:58,082
- I'll put another one in.
- Okay.

775
00:31:58,708 --> 00:31:59,625
1 BALL OUT TO EARN EXTRA

776
00:31:59,626 --> 00:32:00,918
There it goes.

777
00:32:00,919 --> 00:32:02,711
One, two, three…

778
00:32:02,712 --> 00:32:03,921
1 BALL OUT, 7 BALLS IN

779
00:32:03,922 --> 00:32:06,006
There's definitely a formula.

780
00:32:06,007 --> 00:32:07,007
Is that the key?

781
00:32:07,008 --> 00:32:08,842
I want to save the day.

782
00:32:08,843 --> 00:32:11,720
Whoever solves this will be a hero.

783
00:32:11,721 --> 00:32:13,764
<i>I wanted to be the hero.</i>

784
00:32:13,765 --> 00:32:15,974
In order to be the hero,

785
00:32:15,975 --> 00:32:18,268
I had to figure out the formula.

786
00:32:18,269 --> 00:32:20,979
<i>So, I became hyper-focused.</i>

787
00:32:20,980 --> 00:32:23,023
What could this mean?

788
00:32:23,024 --> 00:32:24,524
Ten balls give us zero.

789
00:32:24,525 --> 00:32:26,276
Maybe there's no formula.

790
00:32:26,277 --> 00:32:27,945
There has to be one.

791
00:32:27,946 --> 00:32:29,405
None of the numbers overlap.

792
00:32:30,490 --> 00:32:31,949
None of them overlap?

793
00:32:31,950 --> 00:32:33,200
Should we try more?

794
00:32:33,201 --> 00:32:34,534
- Should we try seven?
- Yes.

795
00:32:34,535 --> 00:32:35,577
Seven?

796
00:32:35,578 --> 00:32:36,787
7 BALLS OUT

797
00:32:36,788 --> 00:32:38,121
I'm flushing seven.

798
00:32:38,122 --> 00:32:44,169
7 BALLS OUT

799
00:32:44,170 --> 00:32:45,462
We've got nine.

800
00:32:45,463 --> 00:32:46,421
Nine balls.

801
00:32:46,422 --> 00:32:48,090
- This feels important.
- I agree.

802
00:32:48,091 --> 00:32:50,259
- Hye-ri, do you have an idea?
- Yes?

803
00:32:50,969 --> 00:32:53,095
Well, the thing is,

804
00:32:53,096 --> 00:32:57,057
we flushed seven and got nine.

805
00:32:57,058 --> 00:33:00,143
Can you flush eight
to see if the output is six?

806
00:33:00,144 --> 00:33:01,061
I'll flush eight.

807
00:33:01,062 --> 00:33:01,979
8 BALLS OUT

808
00:33:01,980 --> 00:33:03,313
Here we go.

809
00:33:03,314 --> 00:33:05,065
8 BALLS OUT

810
00:33:05,066 --> 00:33:06,775
COULD IT BE?

811
00:33:06,776 --> 00:33:07,943
8 BALLS OUT

812
00:33:07,944 --> 00:33:09,611
One, two, three, four, five, six.

813
00:33:09,612 --> 00:33:11,363
- Are there six?
- Yes.

814
00:33:11,364 --> 00:33:12,489
- Have you cracked it?
- Have you?

815
00:33:12,490 --> 00:33:14,282
- Yes.
- What is it?

816
00:33:14,283 --> 00:33:15,868
- If you look here…
- Yes?

817
00:33:16,494 --> 00:33:19,162
…eight plus two is ten.

818
00:33:19,163 --> 00:33:20,956
Nine plus one is ten.

819
00:33:20,957 --> 00:33:22,666
Six plus four is ten.

820
00:33:22,667 --> 00:33:23,625
- You're right.
- Like this.

821
00:33:23,626 --> 00:33:25,293
- The sum is ten?
- Yes.

822
00:33:25,294 --> 00:33:26,878
- They add up to ten.
- You're right.

823
00:33:26,879 --> 00:33:28,130
Since we didn't have paper,

824
00:33:28,131 --> 00:33:31,466
I blew on the mirror
to write down the numbers.

825
00:33:31,467 --> 00:33:32,801
<i>Once I wrote them down,</i>

826
00:33:32,802 --> 00:33:36,430
I started to see a pattern.

827
00:33:36,431 --> 00:33:39,182
- If we flush nine, we'll get three.
- Nine will give us three, right?

828
00:33:39,183 --> 00:33:40,309
Let's check that.

829
00:33:41,019 --> 00:33:42,019
I'm flushing nine.

830
00:33:42,020 --> 00:33:43,521
9 BALLS OUT

831
00:33:44,230 --> 00:33:45,355
That's it.

832
00:33:45,356 --> 00:33:47,691
- We've got three back.
- That's it.

833
00:33:47,692 --> 00:33:49,359
- That's it.
- We cracked it.

834
00:33:49,360 --> 00:33:50,444
It's right.

835
00:33:50,445 --> 00:33:51,987
HERO HYE-RI FINDS THE FORMULA

836
00:33:51,988 --> 00:33:53,740
Great job, Hye-ri.

837
00:33:54,365 --> 00:33:56,658
- But what's the purpose of the pattern?
- Not sure.

838
00:33:56,659 --> 00:33:57,826
Why?

839
00:33:57,827 --> 00:34:01,246
We've come this far,
but now we have to figure out more.

840
00:34:01,247 --> 00:34:03,373
We have no idea what to do with it.

841
00:34:03,374 --> 00:34:05,125
This is so annoying.

842
00:34:05,126 --> 00:34:06,878
I just want to poop in that toilet.

843
00:34:07,712 --> 00:34:09,546
I'm so annoyed.

844
00:34:09,547 --> 00:34:12,090
NO, PLEASE DON'T DO IT

845
00:34:12,091 --> 00:34:14,301
We found the formula,

846
00:34:14,302 --> 00:34:17,304
but we haven't cracked the code.

847
00:34:17,305 --> 00:34:20,432
- Let's use the F1 key.
- But Hye-ri did so well.

848
00:34:20,433 --> 00:34:21,558
Right?

849
00:34:21,559 --> 00:34:25,145
Should we just press the button
and accept whatever happens?

850
00:34:25,146 --> 00:34:27,564
Yeah, let's press it.

851
00:34:27,565 --> 00:34:29,066
Who wants to do it?

852
00:34:29,067 --> 00:34:30,692
DO YOU?

853
00:34:30,693 --> 00:34:33,361
Wait, are you up for it?

854
00:34:33,362 --> 00:34:34,863
I'll do it.

855
00:34:34,864 --> 00:34:37,240
- Let me.
- Let's go, Yong-jin!

856
00:34:37,241 --> 00:34:39,493
PRESSES F1 KEY WITHOUT HESITATION

857
00:34:39,494 --> 00:34:40,952
SCARED

858
00:34:40,953 --> 00:34:42,622
He really pressed it.

859
00:34:45,083 --> 00:34:47,126
"Make the sum of the balls zero"?

860
00:34:48,169 --> 00:34:50,212
We shouldn't be holding onto the balls.

861
00:34:50,213 --> 00:34:51,713
So, if we make ten…

862
00:34:51,714 --> 00:34:54,549
- We need tens.
- Then, we'll have none left over.

863
00:34:54,550 --> 00:35:00,013
The goal was to ensure no balls were left.

864
00:35:00,014 --> 00:35:02,432
- Our lifeline is so depleted.
- It is.

865
00:35:02,433 --> 00:35:05,227
GAUGE DOWN BY 7 BARS

866
00:35:05,228 --> 00:35:08,021
- That's okay. That seems about right.
- You're right.

867
00:35:08,022 --> 00:35:09,981
- How many balls are left?
- We have…

868
00:35:09,982 --> 00:35:10,899
There are ten.

869
00:35:10,900 --> 00:35:12,859
- There are ten, right?
- Yes, there are.

870
00:35:12,860 --> 00:35:14,069
10 BALLS REMAINING

871
00:35:14,070 --> 00:35:15,445
Hurry and put them in.

872
00:35:15,446 --> 00:35:16,947
Come on!

873
00:35:16,948 --> 00:35:18,824
Why didn't we get this sooner?

874
00:35:18,825 --> 00:35:20,951
We didn't think of getting rid of them.

875
00:35:20,952 --> 00:35:22,327
Yeah.

876
00:35:22,328 --> 00:35:23,662
I'm flushing ten.

877
00:35:23,663 --> 00:35:25,455
PUTTING IN ALL 10 BALLS

878
00:35:25,456 --> 00:35:27,958
NO BALLS LEFT
Q-01 MISSION COMPLETE

879
00:35:27,959 --> 00:35:29,918
SUCCESS AT LAST

880
00:35:29,919 --> 00:35:31,128
- It's so anticlimactic.
- Good job.

881
00:35:31,129 --> 00:35:34,089
- Hye-ri, you're the best.
- But we got the formula.

882
00:35:34,090 --> 00:35:35,882
<i>It was a fairly simple solution.</i>

883
00:35:35,883 --> 00:35:38,552
That's why it was so frustrating.

884
00:35:38,553 --> 00:35:40,262
The first room made me realize

885
00:35:40,263 --> 00:35:46,394
it was up to us
to figure out the mission's goal.

886
00:35:46,936 --> 00:35:48,646
Something opened up.

887
00:35:50,022 --> 00:35:51,273
KEY CARD TO ROOM 108

888
00:35:51,274 --> 00:35:52,232
Yes, it did.

889
00:35:52,233 --> 00:35:53,650
Let's go to the next room.

890
00:35:53,651 --> 00:35:56,028
- I'll solve it really quickly.
- This is so hard.

891
00:35:56,654 --> 00:35:58,865
- I'll be so quick.
- But what is that?

892
00:36:01,075 --> 00:36:03,286
- What is it?
- What's happening?

893
00:36:12,587 --> 00:36:13,963
UFO?

894
00:36:24,891 --> 00:36:27,684
Did they just say there was an alien?

895
00:36:27,685 --> 00:36:28,935
- Sorry?
- An alien.

896
00:36:28,936 --> 00:36:30,270
I didn't catch anything.

897
00:36:30,271 --> 00:36:34,441
A new species of… Life…

898
00:36:34,442 --> 00:36:37,110
It seemed like a UFO
sank into the sea.

899
00:36:37,111 --> 00:36:38,403
<i>I felt a bit lost.</i>

900
00:36:38,404 --> 00:36:39,654
I didn't get what was happening.

901
00:36:39,655 --> 00:36:42,032
It was definitely strange.

902
00:36:42,033 --> 00:36:44,618
Did it contain a clue
about the Black Room?

903
00:36:44,619 --> 00:36:48,163
I didn't catch every word.
But they mentioned a "new species."

904
00:36:48,164 --> 00:36:52,459
- Did they?
- A new type of lifeform.

905
00:36:52,460 --> 00:36:54,045
It's scary.

906
00:36:54,879 --> 00:36:57,839
THE SCAREDY-CAT YOUNGEST LEADS THE WAY

907
00:36:57,840 --> 00:36:59,133
It's Room 108.

908
00:36:59,675 --> 00:37:00,592
Which room?

909
00:37:00,593 --> 00:37:02,136
- Room 108.
- Room 108?

910
00:37:03,971 --> 00:37:05,932
What is it?

911
00:37:07,058 --> 00:37:09,517
A CLUSTER OF DOTS

912
00:37:09,518 --> 00:37:12,270
We need to match these dots.

913
00:37:12,271 --> 00:37:14,689
There are three-dot, six-dot,
and two-dot clusters.

914
00:37:14,690 --> 00:37:16,107
The dots should align like this.

915
00:37:16,108 --> 00:37:17,734
- The number of dots has to match.
- Yes.

916
00:37:17,735 --> 00:37:19,027
Karina's good at this.

917
00:37:19,028 --> 00:37:20,278
It's at the very bottom.

918
00:37:20,279 --> 00:37:21,905
Yes, that's the one.

919
00:37:21,906 --> 00:37:23,282
The six dots at the bottom.

920
00:37:23,908 --> 00:37:24,824
This one?

921
00:37:24,825 --> 00:37:26,285
Yeah. Right?

922
00:37:27,245 --> 00:37:29,454
- That's a three-dot cluster.
- This doesn't match.

923
00:37:29,455 --> 00:37:31,414
These don't match.

924
00:37:31,415 --> 00:37:33,208
4 DOTS VS 3 DOTS

925
00:37:33,209 --> 00:37:34,960
Why are there so many six-dot clusters?

926
00:37:34,961 --> 00:37:36,044
DOTSTALT BREAKDOWN

927
00:37:36,045 --> 00:37:38,547
What about these six?

928
00:37:39,632 --> 00:37:40,675
Maybe if we flip it?

929
00:37:43,010 --> 00:37:44,552
It doesn't match. My bad.

930
00:37:44,553 --> 00:37:46,054
CHUCKLE

931
00:37:46,055 --> 00:37:47,555
This is so hard.

932
00:37:47,556 --> 00:37:48,724
It's this one.

933
00:37:49,809 --> 00:37:52,602
HYE-RI'S CHOICE

934
00:37:52,603 --> 00:37:53,980
I think that's right.

935
00:37:58,276 --> 00:38:00,361
- Do they match?
- Yes, this is it.

936
00:38:01,320 --> 00:38:02,362
What's the number?

937
00:38:02,363 --> 00:38:04,406
COUNT THE DOTS IN THE BOXES

938
00:38:04,407 --> 00:38:07,826
Nine, one, eight.

939
00:38:07,827 --> 00:38:09,828
- One, two, three, four, five, six, seven.
- Seven.

940
00:38:09,829 --> 00:38:11,663
- Want to try it?
- Is it right?

941
00:38:11,664 --> 00:38:12,623
Let's try.

942
00:38:14,083 --> 00:38:15,293
Nine, seven, one, eight.

943
00:38:15,960 --> 00:38:16,794
It worked.

944
00:38:18,170 --> 00:38:19,713
- It's the same.
- Again?

945
00:38:19,714 --> 00:38:21,131
That's just how…

946
00:38:21,132 --> 00:38:22,465
- What is this?
- What on earth?

947
00:38:22,466 --> 00:38:25,885
<i>We went in the room,
and the layout was almost identical.</i>

948
00:38:25,886 --> 00:38:27,137
IDENTICAL TO THE FIRST ROOM

949
00:38:27,138 --> 00:38:30,348
We're still stuck in Q-01!

950
00:38:30,349 --> 00:38:32,017
So, that's not very important.

951
00:38:32,018 --> 00:38:34,394
- Right.
- We just need to solve the puzzles.

952
00:38:34,395 --> 00:38:36,730
- It just means this is stage two.
- Come on.

953
00:38:36,731 --> 00:38:38,898
We wasted time on it for nothing?

954
00:38:38,899 --> 00:38:39,941
It's okay.

955
00:38:39,942 --> 00:38:44,237
- There's an F1 button in every room.
- You're right.

956
00:38:44,238 --> 00:38:46,574
I CAN ASSIST AT ANY TIME!

957
00:38:47,450 --> 00:38:50,953
- What do you think this is?
- What is this?

958
00:38:51,871 --> 00:38:53,163
A MYSTERIOUS TABLE

959
00:38:53,164 --> 00:38:54,497
What is it?

960
00:38:54,498 --> 00:38:55,665
What do we do?

961
00:38:55,666 --> 00:38:56,624
KNOCK KNOCK

962
00:38:56,625 --> 00:39:01,046
There were six lanes,
and there was a ball in each lane.

963
00:39:01,047 --> 00:39:04,508
<i>And there was a dip at each end.</i>

964
00:39:05,259 --> 00:39:07,344
Can we lift it? It's not movable, is it?

965
00:39:07,345 --> 00:39:09,137
UP IT GOES

966
00:39:09,138 --> 00:39:11,264
- Never mind.
- I don't think this will work.

967
00:39:11,265 --> 00:39:12,475
I don't think so.

968
00:39:13,642 --> 00:39:17,687
There are six in total, so…

969
00:39:17,688 --> 00:39:19,189
Where was this ball at the start?

970
00:39:19,190 --> 00:39:20,941
- It was here.
- Here?

971
00:39:21,859 --> 00:39:24,235
We need to get them to the ends.

972
00:39:24,236 --> 00:39:25,570
Is that possible?

973
00:39:25,571 --> 00:39:27,572
We need to get the balls in to solve this.

974
00:39:27,573 --> 00:39:28,907
- Right?
- Yeah.

975
00:39:28,908 --> 00:39:30,158
We needed to work as a team

976
00:39:30,159 --> 00:39:34,120
and move the balls in one go
to win the mission.

977
00:39:34,121 --> 00:39:36,414
We need to get them here
to complete the mission.

978
00:39:36,415 --> 00:39:37,457
It seems like it.

979
00:39:37,458 --> 00:39:39,501
So, how do we get them over there?

980
00:39:39,502 --> 00:39:41,294
I don't suppose they're magnets?

981
00:39:41,295 --> 00:39:45,633
- I think these are.
- They seem like it.

982
00:39:47,009 --> 00:39:49,886
THE CHOKERS AREN'T MAGNETS

983
00:39:49,887 --> 00:39:51,763
I thought they might be magnets.

984
00:39:51,764 --> 00:39:55,600
Or maybe there was something
on our uniforms

985
00:39:55,601 --> 00:39:59,230
that we could use to tug them.

986
00:40:02,149 --> 00:40:04,276
ACQUIRED A BELT STRAP

987
00:40:04,985 --> 00:40:06,027
TRIES SLIDING

988
00:40:06,028 --> 00:40:07,029
NO MOVEMENT

989
00:40:09,865 --> 00:40:11,866
JOHN PARK JOINS IN

990
00:40:11,867 --> 00:40:12,909
MAGNETIE

991
00:40:12,910 --> 00:40:14,787
I tried that earlier.

992
00:40:15,871 --> 00:40:17,705
We all think alike.

993
00:40:17,706 --> 00:40:20,166
Can't we use centrifugal force?

994
00:40:20,167 --> 00:40:24,170
If we turn the table,
the balls might fly outward.

995
00:40:24,171 --> 00:40:26,257
But there are six balls.

996
00:40:26,882 --> 00:40:29,008
- Could we…
- Can we really not lift it?

997
00:40:29,009 --> 00:40:30,885
It won't budge, will it?

998
00:40:30,886 --> 00:40:32,720
No, I don't think so.

999
00:40:32,721 --> 00:40:36,433
But if it's not nailed down,
we can lift it.

1000
00:40:36,434 --> 00:40:40,186
Maybe we can get the balls in
by making the table level.

1001
00:40:40,187 --> 00:40:44,107
Right, but let's say
we're not supposed to lift it.

1002
00:40:44,108 --> 00:40:47,694
Then, why are there
four legs for stability?

1003
00:40:47,695 --> 00:40:49,529
Wait, I'm sure we can lift it.

1004
00:40:49,530 --> 00:40:51,781
- It's not nailed down.
- Right?

1005
00:40:51,782 --> 00:40:55,077
- Then, Gabee might be right.
- Maybe we turn it.

1006
00:40:55,995 --> 00:40:57,787
- Which way?
- Okay, to the right.

1007
00:40:57,788 --> 00:41:00,123
- Like this?
- We need to go way faster.

1008
00:41:00,124 --> 00:41:01,499
I feel dizzy.

1009
00:41:01,500 --> 00:41:02,834
We need to spin really fast.

1010
00:41:02,835 --> 00:41:04,461
- That's it.
- We have to move fast.

1011
00:41:04,462 --> 00:41:05,545
Faster.

1012
00:41:05,546 --> 00:41:07,465
- Let go.
- Stop.

1013
00:41:08,174 --> 00:41:09,550
That's it.

1014
00:41:10,968 --> 00:41:12,385
- Let's go again.
- Let's go.

1015
00:41:12,386 --> 00:41:14,762
- Let's try again.
- This feels right.

1016
00:41:14,763 --> 00:41:15,930
I'm so dizzy.

1017
00:41:15,931 --> 00:41:17,266
Should we change direction?

1018
00:41:18,142 --> 00:41:19,559
I feel so dizzy!

1019
00:41:19,560 --> 00:41:21,603
Just a little more! Gently!

1020
00:41:21,604 --> 00:41:23,980
- Go slowly.
- Just Do-hoon and Hye-ri slow down.

1021
00:41:23,981 --> 00:41:25,815
Just for Hye-ri and Do-hoon.

1022
00:41:25,816 --> 00:41:27,942
Oh, no.

1023
00:41:27,943 --> 00:41:28,985
- No, Karina.
- Oh, no.

1024
00:41:28,986 --> 00:41:30,445
This is hard.

1025
00:41:30,446 --> 00:41:31,905
Move it toward John.

1026
00:41:31,906 --> 00:41:33,323
BACK INTO PLACE

1027
00:41:33,324 --> 00:41:34,241
Let go.

1028
00:41:35,451 --> 00:41:36,659
This is hard.

1029
00:41:36,660 --> 00:41:38,161
But I think this is the right way.

1030
00:41:38,162 --> 00:41:40,455
- Same.
- Gabee, you were so right.

1031
00:41:40,456 --> 00:41:43,209
- Centrifugation.
- You did great, Gabee.

1032
00:41:44,543 --> 00:41:47,045
The key is to keep the table level.

1033
00:41:47,046 --> 00:41:49,756
- That's the key.
- It needs to be level.

1034
00:41:49,757 --> 00:41:52,008
And once we're done turning it,

1035
00:41:52,009 --> 00:41:54,886
- we need to stabilize it.
- You're right.

1036
00:41:54,887 --> 00:41:57,013
- Should we try it?
- Let's change direction.

1037
00:41:57,014 --> 00:41:58,348
Let's keep it level.

1038
00:41:58,349 --> 00:41:59,975
- Ready? Go!
- Ready? Go!

1039
00:42:01,519 --> 00:42:03,561
HUMAN SPINNING WHEEL

1040
00:42:03,562 --> 00:42:04,479
Let's go.

1041
00:42:04,480 --> 00:42:05,314
Be careful.

1042
00:42:05,898 --> 00:42:08,900
Now, slow down. Keep it level.

1043
00:42:08,901 --> 00:42:10,235
We can't let it bounce.

1044
00:42:10,236 --> 00:42:13,279
- It can't bounce.
- Let's stop slowly.

1045
00:42:13,280 --> 00:42:14,948
- We can spin slowly.
- Yes, we can.

1046
00:42:14,949 --> 00:42:16,824
We're nearly there.

1047
00:42:16,825 --> 00:42:17,742
There we go.

1048
00:42:17,743 --> 00:42:20,120
- Oh, Do-hoon!
- Oh, no.

1049
00:42:21,080 --> 00:42:26,584
- Wait, it's coming back.
- I think we can move it slowly.

1050
00:42:26,585 --> 00:42:28,378
We don't need to go quickly.

1051
00:42:28,379 --> 00:42:30,838
- The ball will find its way.
- Amazing. It's so scientific.

1052
00:42:30,839 --> 00:42:32,048
- Careful.
- Be careful.

1053
00:42:32,049 --> 00:42:34,217
- We did it.
- Stop slowly.

1054
00:42:34,218 --> 00:42:35,636
- Stop.
- They're all in.

1055
00:42:36,345 --> 00:42:37,345
Q-02
MISSION SUCCESSFUL

1056
00:42:37,346 --> 00:42:39,265
- We did it!
- It worked!

1057
00:42:41,559 --> 00:42:43,017
WELL DONE AGENT QUEEN GABEE

1058
00:42:43,018 --> 00:42:44,936
This was…

1059
00:42:44,937 --> 00:42:47,397
- Gabee, you're good at this.
- Unbelievable.

1060
00:42:47,398 --> 00:42:48,691
You're good.

1061
00:42:49,358 --> 00:42:51,025
<i>I felt encouraged.</i>

1062
00:42:51,026 --> 00:42:52,485
Even though she's new,

1063
00:42:52,486 --> 00:42:57,241
she has great instincts and ideas.

1064
00:42:58,909 --> 00:43:01,412
<i>Hello, this is Oracle.</i>

1065
00:43:02,204 --> 00:43:06,625
<i>I have an important announcement
that requires your attention.</i>

1066
00:43:08,252 --> 00:43:11,129
<i>The indicator on the side of the screen</i>

1067
00:43:11,130 --> 00:43:14,382
<i>shows the security level
of the Black Room.</i>

1068
00:43:14,383 --> 00:43:18,845
- Oh, it's a safety alert.
<i>- If you get help with the F1 button,</i>

1069
00:43:18,846 --> 00:43:22,849
<i>or spend too much time on one level,</i>

1070
00:43:22,850 --> 00:43:26,603
<i>Black Room security will weaken.</i>

1071
00:43:26,604 --> 00:43:30,023
<i>The gauge will decrease accordingly.</i>

1072
00:43:30,024 --> 00:43:32,609
<i>When it reaches the depletion stage,</i>

1073
00:43:32,610 --> 00:43:35,653
<i>logged-in agents
will be recognized as hackers,</i>

1074
00:43:35,654 --> 00:43:40,199
<i>and the Attacker neutralization protocol
will be automatically activated.</i>

1075
00:43:40,200 --> 00:43:42,118
<i>Once the protocol is activated,</i>

1076
00:43:42,119 --> 00:43:46,623
<i>security agents called Trackers
will be immediately mobilized.</i>

1077
00:43:46,624 --> 00:43:50,710
<i>To make sure you understand
the seriousness of this protocol,</i>

1078
00:43:50,711 --> 00:43:54,631
<i>we will show
the Attacker neutralization protocol</i>

1079
00:43:54,632 --> 00:43:58,427
<i>in action against intruders.</i>

1080
00:44:06,143 --> 00:44:11,231
<i>They seemed to be people
who were in a similar position to us.</i>

1081
00:44:13,984 --> 00:44:15,778
<i>Unknown figures were chasing them.</i>

1082
00:44:17,154 --> 00:44:19,572
<i>There were a lot of defense agents.</i>

1083
00:44:19,573 --> 00:44:21,283
<i>I'd say there were ten of them.</i>

1084
00:44:35,547 --> 00:44:37,925
<i>They dragged them to the room at the end.</i>

1085
00:44:39,843 --> 00:44:41,553
<i>They were locked up.</i>

1086
00:44:43,889 --> 00:44:48,769
<i>They were in a room with walls
made of bricks and without any doors.</i>

1087
00:44:52,940 --> 00:44:57,027
- What's that?
<i>- Bricks tumbled down from above.</i>

1088
00:45:01,824 --> 00:45:04,033
- Oh, no!
- That must be how they die.

1089
00:45:04,034 --> 00:45:05,701
For the first time,

1090
00:45:05,702 --> 00:45:10,082
I realized we weren't safe
wandering around freely here.

1091
00:45:24,596 --> 00:45:25,763
What just happened?

1092
00:45:25,764 --> 00:45:27,682
- They turned to dust.
- Everything vanished.

1093
00:45:27,683 --> 00:45:29,600
- Did something explode?
- They were vaporized.

1094
00:45:29,601 --> 00:45:30,853
They were burned up.

1095
00:45:33,313 --> 00:45:34,772
This is so scary.

1096
00:45:34,773 --> 00:45:37,066
I'm scared to open this door and go out.

1097
00:45:37,067 --> 00:45:38,444
It's Room 115.

1098
00:45:40,320 --> 00:45:44,991
- What could this be?
- I think it's like the game Go.

1099
00:45:44,992 --> 00:45:47,076
THE KEY CARD HAS 4 NUMBERS

1100
00:45:47,077 --> 00:45:48,161
I have no idea.

1101
00:45:48,162 --> 00:45:51,789
Does 74 fit into some kind of formula?

1102
00:45:51,790 --> 00:45:54,333
It might be like the rules of Go.

1103
00:45:54,334 --> 00:45:56,711
It could be different number moves.

1104
00:45:56,712 --> 00:45:58,921
- Does anyone know how to play Go?
- The order.

1105
00:45:58,922 --> 00:46:01,717
Where is 74?

1106
00:46:02,342 --> 00:46:05,720
- Here.
- If you put this on 74,

1107
00:46:05,721 --> 00:46:07,597
we should see something.

1108
00:46:07,598 --> 00:46:13,102
Maybe we need to count
the black and white stones.

1109
00:46:13,103 --> 00:46:16,272
- There are five of each.
- So, that's five.

1110
00:46:16,273 --> 00:46:17,482
What if we put it on 20?

1111
00:46:17,483 --> 00:46:18,733
POSITIONING BY ORDER

1112
00:46:18,734 --> 00:46:20,651
- That's right, isn't it?
- Five of each.

1113
00:46:20,652 --> 00:46:22,403
Five of each.

1114
00:46:22,404 --> 00:46:24,030
- It's five again?
- Yeah.

1115
00:46:24,031 --> 00:46:25,115
Sixty-six.

1116
00:46:27,618 --> 00:46:29,327
It must be 5556 or 5554.

1117
00:46:29,328 --> 00:46:30,578
It's 5556 or 5554?

1118
00:46:30,579 --> 00:46:32,664
TRYING 5556

1119
00:46:33,457 --> 00:46:34,373
Try 5554.

1120
00:46:34,374 --> 00:46:36,043
TRYING 5554

1121
00:46:36,627 --> 00:46:37,669
That's not it.

1122
00:46:47,054 --> 00:46:48,262
You found it?

1123
00:46:48,263 --> 00:46:53,018
We should focus on missing numbers,
not written numbers.

1124
00:46:54,186 --> 00:46:55,812
<i>I pictured it as a keypad.</i>

1125
00:46:57,022 --> 00:46:58,731
There's a blank space.

1126
00:46:58,732 --> 00:47:00,399
- Nine.
- Nine.

1127
00:47:00,400 --> 00:47:01,693
- Next is zero.
- Zero.

1128
00:47:03,320 --> 00:47:04,695
- Four.
- Four.

1129
00:47:04,696 --> 00:47:06,072
What is it?

1130
00:47:06,073 --> 00:47:07,533
- Nine, zero, four, one.
- One.

1131
00:47:11,161 --> 00:47:12,620
HYE-RI DID IT AGAIN

1132
00:47:12,621 --> 00:47:14,997
- You're awesome.
- You're a genius!

1133
00:47:14,998 --> 00:47:18,042
<i>Once again, the Gate Master Hye-ri…</i>

1134
00:47:18,043 --> 00:47:19,127
LAUGHS

1135
00:47:20,003 --> 00:47:20,963
I helped out.

1136
00:47:23,882 --> 00:47:25,509
I'm glad I could help.

1137
00:47:27,469 --> 00:47:30,513
- It seems very…
- There is something.

1138
00:47:30,514 --> 00:47:32,682
<i>There was a tablet.</i>

1139
00:47:32,683 --> 00:47:34,433
We needed to find something
to write on it.

1140
00:47:34,434 --> 00:47:36,644
So, we looked around.

1141
00:47:36,645 --> 00:47:38,438
- It seems very…
- What is this?

1142
00:47:39,314 --> 00:47:40,982
This is…

1143
00:47:40,983 --> 00:47:41,817
- What is it?
- A cross?

1144
00:47:42,609 --> 00:47:43,734
Is it a direction?

1145
00:47:43,735 --> 00:47:45,611
There's an arrow here.

1146
00:47:45,612 --> 00:47:46,821
They're Chinese characters.

1147
00:47:46,822 --> 00:47:50,157
On the glass panes, there were symbols

1148
00:47:50,158 --> 00:47:53,077
that looked like Chinese characters,

1149
00:47:53,078 --> 00:47:56,205
<i>but they seemed only half-written.</i>

1150
00:47:56,206 --> 00:47:57,791
What room was this?

1151
00:48:01,211 --> 00:48:02,754
- What is that?
- What is it?

1152
00:48:04,923 --> 00:48:06,133
What was that?

1153
00:48:07,551 --> 00:48:08,969
A ghost appeared.

1154
00:48:11,638 --> 00:48:14,056
SHOWS UP ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE

1155
00:48:14,057 --> 00:48:16,058
- Please, I hate ghosts.
- I hate this.

1156
00:48:16,059 --> 00:48:17,602
- What is this?
- I can't handle ghosts.

1157
00:48:17,603 --> 00:48:19,645
The ghost keeps showing up

1158
00:48:19,646 --> 00:48:21,148
where there's a Chinese character.

1159
00:48:21,982 --> 00:48:23,941
A GHOST FOR EVERY CHARACTER?

1160
00:48:23,942 --> 00:48:24,984
ANOTHER RED CHARACTER

1161
00:48:24,985 --> 00:48:27,028
Will it show here too? Hello.

1162
00:48:27,029 --> 00:48:28,696
He's crazy.

1163
00:48:28,697 --> 00:48:30,490
HELLO

1164
00:48:32,451 --> 00:48:33,367
SCREAMING

1165
00:48:33,368 --> 00:48:34,202
He's right.

1166
00:48:36,163 --> 00:48:37,873
FRIGHTENED

1167
00:48:39,166 --> 00:48:40,625
You said "Hello"!

1168
00:48:40,626 --> 00:48:43,085
- That one!
- The character…

1169
00:48:43,086 --> 00:48:47,549
I knew it would happen,
but I was still terrified.

1170
00:48:48,550 --> 00:48:51,010
<i>My heart nearly jumped out of my chest.</i>

1171
00:48:51,011 --> 00:48:52,053
That one!

1172
00:48:52,054 --> 00:48:53,429
- Are you okay?
- That hasn't shown.

1173
00:48:53,430 --> 00:48:54,472
What about that side?

1174
00:48:54,473 --> 00:48:55,556
- It was here earlier.
- It was.

1175
00:48:55,557 --> 00:48:56,849
- Was it?
- You were over there.

1176
00:48:56,850 --> 00:48:57,808
I missed it?

1177
00:48:57,809 --> 00:48:59,602
It popped up while you were screaming.

1178
00:48:59,603 --> 00:49:00,770
Look at that.

1179
00:49:00,771 --> 00:49:02,355
It's a Chinese character.

1180
00:49:02,356 --> 00:49:04,565
- It's the character for "ten."
- That's right.

1181
00:49:04,566 --> 00:49:05,775
- Doesn't that mean "son"?
- Yes

1182
00:49:05,776 --> 00:49:07,610
- "Son" has another line.
- It's turned off.

1183
00:49:07,611 --> 00:49:10,529
You're right. Please turn back on.

1184
00:49:10,530 --> 00:49:11,864
Will it appear here?

1185
00:49:11,865 --> 00:49:13,449
BLACKOUT

1186
00:49:13,450 --> 00:49:14,743
- Please!
- Can you see?

1187
00:49:20,082 --> 00:49:21,083
Hey!

1188
00:49:21,583 --> 00:49:23,084
Wait!

1189
00:49:23,085 --> 00:49:25,336
SCARED WITLESS

1190
00:49:25,337 --> 00:49:27,506
PANDEMONIUM

1191
00:49:28,799 --> 00:49:30,257
Hey!

1192
00:49:30,258 --> 00:49:32,009
- Hold on!
- What's going on?

1193
00:49:32,010 --> 00:49:34,011
- Where is it?
- I hate this!

1194
00:49:34,012 --> 00:49:36,013
- Help!
- I hate this!

1195
00:49:36,014 --> 00:49:37,515
Come this way!

1196
00:49:37,516 --> 00:49:40,102
- Help!
- Come over here!

1197
00:49:40,811 --> 00:49:43,020
- Go away.
- Where did it go?

1198
00:49:43,021 --> 00:49:44,105
IT DISAPPEARED

1199
00:49:44,106 --> 00:49:46,942
- Seriously.
- What the heck?

1200
00:49:47,609 --> 00:49:49,945
I said no ghosts!

1201
00:49:51,196 --> 00:49:53,614
<i>I can't watch horror movies.</i>

1202
00:49:53,615 --> 00:49:58,078
I was once in a horror movie,
and I was scared filming it.

1203
00:49:59,079 --> 00:50:01,789
It got dark, and the lights kept flashing.

1204
00:50:01,790 --> 00:50:04,834
I hated it with a passion.

1205
00:50:04,835 --> 00:50:06,085
I was so scared.

1206
00:50:06,086 --> 00:50:08,338
At least you stuck together.

1207
00:50:08,922 --> 00:50:09,839
I was all alone.

1208
00:50:09,840 --> 00:50:11,215
THEY WERE TOGETHER AT FIRST

1209
00:50:11,216 --> 00:50:13,134
- Wait!
- What's going on?

1210
00:50:13,135 --> 00:50:14,969
I couldn't feel anything.

1211
00:50:14,970 --> 00:50:16,972
BUT ENDED UP ALONE

1212
00:50:19,599 --> 00:50:21,225
I mean, seriously…

1213
00:50:21,226 --> 00:50:22,727
LAUGHING OUT OF FEAR

1214
00:50:22,728 --> 00:50:25,105
Help!

1215
00:50:25,981 --> 00:50:27,898
Help!

1216
00:50:27,899 --> 00:50:34,865
This reality show
can be a scary experience.

1217
00:50:35,574 --> 00:50:38,284
- My heart's pounding.
- Where did it come from?

1218
00:50:38,285 --> 00:50:40,161
Where did it come from?

1219
00:50:40,162 --> 00:50:42,705
Where did it come from,
and where did it go?

1220
00:50:42,706 --> 00:50:44,999
I seriously can't do ghosts.

1221
00:50:45,000 --> 00:50:46,333
So, what was that?

1222
00:50:46,334 --> 00:50:47,460
What was it?

1223
00:50:47,461 --> 00:50:50,254
Why did a ghost show up?

1224
00:50:50,255 --> 00:50:53,966
AFTER CALMING DOWN
FINALLY AN ATTEMPT TO USE THE TABLET

1225
00:50:53,967 --> 00:50:57,344
Whatever you write shows up on the screen.

1226
00:50:57,345 --> 00:50:58,679
So, that's how it works.

1227
00:50:58,680 --> 00:51:00,806
Should we write the Chinese characters?

1228
00:51:00,807 --> 00:51:03,517
First, there's an order, right?

1229
00:51:03,518 --> 00:51:04,435
That one's first.

1230
00:51:04,436 --> 00:51:05,437
"Ten."

1231
00:51:06,897 --> 00:51:08,940
This one, that one,
and the one over there.

1232
00:51:12,527 --> 00:51:15,404
THEY WRITE THE RED CHARACTERS
IN ORDER OF DISCOVERY

1233
00:51:15,405 --> 00:51:18,199
What Chinese characters do they look like?

1234
00:51:18,200 --> 00:51:20,160
Ten people's…

1235
00:51:20,702 --> 00:51:22,953
- Oh, hey.
- When they are put together…

1236
00:51:22,954 --> 00:51:25,207
- What is it?
- When you combine them…

1237
00:51:25,916 --> 00:51:26,875
Look.

1238
00:51:27,584 --> 00:51:29,585
If you combine them, it looks like this.

1239
00:51:29,586 --> 00:51:31,253
It's the sign for "Lee."

1240
00:51:31,254 --> 00:51:32,880
It's the surname Lee.

1241
00:51:32,881 --> 00:51:35,883
- It's the surname.
- Yong-jin, you're right.

1242
00:51:35,884 --> 00:51:37,885
- It's Lee.
- We need to rewrite them.

1243
00:51:37,886 --> 00:51:40,179
It's the character for Lee.

1244
00:51:40,180 --> 00:51:44,725
When you combined
the characters on the walls,

1245
00:51:44,726 --> 00:51:47,645
you got the character for "Lee."

1246
00:51:47,646 --> 00:51:50,564
It happens to be my surname.

1247
00:51:50,565 --> 00:51:52,692
- Yong-jin.
- Yes, it's Lee.

1248
00:51:53,360 --> 00:51:55,319
You're like a Joseon scholar.

1249
00:51:55,320 --> 00:51:56,571
I'm the root of wisdom.

1250
00:51:57,697 --> 00:52:01,992
- Elders know Chinese characters best.
- It's Lee.

1251
00:52:01,993 --> 00:52:05,454
REWRITING THE LETTERS COMBINED

1252
00:52:05,455 --> 00:52:07,456
DID THE ELDERLY KING OF CHINESE CHARACTERS

1253
00:52:07,457 --> 00:52:09,376
IS IT CORRECT?

1254
00:52:11,086 --> 00:52:12,628
<i>I was wrong.</i>

1255
00:52:12,629 --> 00:52:17,758
I was sure the solution
was combining the characters.

1256
00:52:17,759 --> 00:52:19,301
But I was wrong.

1257
00:52:19,302 --> 00:52:21,346
How could that be?

1258
00:52:22,264 --> 00:52:25,224
But doesn't that character
need an extra stroke?

1259
00:52:25,225 --> 00:52:27,184
Oh, you're right.

1260
00:52:27,185 --> 00:52:29,728
- What does it need?
- Another stroke.

1261
00:52:29,729 --> 00:52:32,648
<i>I thought an extra stroke was needed</i>

1262
00:52:32,649 --> 00:52:36,026
for the Chinese character for "Lee."

1263
00:52:36,027 --> 00:52:38,070
There are no more red characters, right?

1264
00:52:38,071 --> 00:52:39,613
- A stroke is…
- We're missing a stroke.

1265
00:52:39,614 --> 00:52:42,741
IS THERE A MISSING CHARACTER?

1266
00:52:42,742 --> 00:52:45,327
- That scared me.
- I think that was your reflection.

1267
00:52:45,328 --> 00:52:46,954
Your own face scared you?

1268
00:52:46,955 --> 00:52:48,873
Come on, Do-hoon.

1269
00:52:48,874 --> 00:52:50,708
That's a bit much.

1270
00:52:50,709 --> 00:52:54,503
- I'll just lie down for a bit.
- You told me to trust you.

1271
00:52:54,504 --> 00:52:56,547
- You said I could rely on you.
- He lied.

1272
00:52:56,548 --> 00:52:57,882
A DEEP SIGH

1273
00:52:57,883 --> 00:53:00,801
Was the last ghost just a fun surprise?

1274
00:53:00,802 --> 00:53:02,137
It was just a performance.

1275
00:53:02,804 --> 00:53:05,055
IT WAS A BIT MUCH

1276
00:53:05,056 --> 00:53:07,308
FOR A SIMPLE PERFORMANCE

1277
00:53:07,309 --> 00:53:09,435
It wasn't a clue, right?

1278
00:53:09,436 --> 00:53:11,104
Was there a letter on that lady?

1279
00:53:12,939 --> 00:53:14,440
Hey!

1280
00:53:14,441 --> 00:53:17,110
A LETTER WAS ON THE FLOOR BY HER FOOT

1281
00:53:18,862 --> 00:53:22,573
THEY MISSED IT WHILE RUNNING AWAY

1282
00:53:22,574 --> 00:53:24,159
Should we write "Lee" in Korean?

1283
00:53:24,951 --> 00:53:27,953
- You need to add another stroke.
- The character for "one"?

1284
00:53:27,954 --> 00:53:29,622
- Stroke like this?
- Yes.

1285
00:53:29,623 --> 00:53:30,749
The Chinese character for "one."

1286
00:53:33,835 --> 00:53:35,961
Yes, it needs another stroke.

1287
00:53:35,962 --> 00:53:38,339
It's right!

1288
00:53:38,340 --> 00:53:39,548
I knew it!

1289
00:53:39,549 --> 00:53:42,968
- What's going on?
- That's the answer.

1290
00:53:42,969 --> 00:53:46,180
- I was right.
- Yong-jin, that was awesome.

1291
00:53:46,181 --> 00:53:47,641
Nice, it was Chinese characters.

1292
00:53:49,184 --> 00:53:51,894
THE KEY CARD FOR THE NEXT ROOM

1293
00:53:51,895 --> 00:53:53,854
I feel so drained.

1294
00:53:53,855 --> 00:53:56,732
I've done my part for today.

1295
00:53:56,733 --> 00:53:58,484
When it comes to Chinese characters…

1296
00:53:58,485 --> 00:54:00,235
I could use a strong drink.

1297
00:54:00,236 --> 00:54:02,279
Yong-jin got it right.

1298
00:54:02,280 --> 00:54:03,615
He's "Lee Yong-jin."

1299
00:54:04,574 --> 00:54:05,866
His surname is Lee.

1300
00:54:05,867 --> 00:54:06,951
Lee Yong-jin.

1301
00:54:06,952 --> 00:54:08,077
Your surname is also Lee.

1302
00:54:08,078 --> 00:54:11,121
My name is just Hye-ri in this show.

1303
00:54:11,122 --> 00:54:13,248
- Let's go.
- Let's go!

1304
00:54:13,249 --> 00:54:15,709
- Is the Lee family involved?
- I think so.

1305
00:54:15,710 --> 00:54:17,753
Nothing else has been relevant.

1306
00:54:17,754 --> 00:54:21,006
I think it was
just the mission for this room.

1307
00:54:21,007 --> 00:54:21,924
- Right?
- Yes.

1308
00:54:21,925 --> 00:54:24,343
- Let's not think too deeply.
- Let's not overthink.

1309
00:54:24,344 --> 00:54:26,553
- That ghost was…
- Next up, room 202.

1310
00:54:26,554 --> 00:54:28,722
What could it be?

1311
00:54:28,723 --> 00:54:30,265
- Are we getting close?
- I was really…

1312
00:54:30,266 --> 00:54:31,351
We need Hye-ri.

1313
00:56:21,127 --> 00:56:26,132
Subtitle translation by: Hannah Og Nam
